    "87": {
      "title": "Or",
      "source": "AI Daily Brief (Nathaniel Whittemore)",
      "host": null,
      "date": "10 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T05",
        "T23"
      ],
      "summary": "Claude Code Review multi-agent PR review at $15–25/PR triggers massive developer backlash — sticker shock compounded by existential response. Boris Tain: 'The Software Development Lifecycle is Dead' — SDLC stages didn't get faster, they merged; intent → agent → does it work? is the new loop. Ankit Jain: 'Human-written code died in 2025. Code reviews will die in 2026.' Teams with high AI adoption: 21% more tasks, 98% more PRs, but 91% more review time — 'We cannot consume this much code.' Whittemore: 'Watching the last part of the sandcastle washed away.' Key structural insight: inference costs starting to look like labour costs, not software costs. Sourcegraph CEO: 'If CTOs can't deliver headcount savings, we're going to see real whiplash on token budgets in 2–4 quarters.' NVIDIA NemoClaw: enterprise OpenClaw platform. Microsoft Copilot Co-Work built on Anthropic technology (<2 months after Claude Co-Work launch). AMI Labs (LeCun): $1B seed, Europe's largest ever. OpenAI acquires PromptFoo (AI security). Core evidence for T05 and T23.",
      "keyThemes": "Claude Code Review launch ($15–25/PR), SDLC death, code review as professional identity, inference-as-labour-cost, enterprise AI budget pressure, NemoClaw (NVIDIA), Microsoft Copilot Co-Work",
      "postPotential": "very-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/The-Debate-Over-Anthropics-New-Product-Price-or-Existential-Dread-e3g8e49"
    },
    "88": {
      "title": "Prompting just split into 4 different skills",
      "source": "Nate’s Newsletter (Substack)",
      "host": null,
      "date": "10 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T03",
        "T26"
      ],
      "summary": "Prompting has split into four distinct disciplines: (1) chatting (table stakes), (2) specification engineering (structured specs for autonomous agents), (3) intent framework building (defining what 'good' means), (4) eval harness construction (scoring systems). Key structural insight: 'The models stopped being conversation partners and started being workers. Workers that run for hours, then days, without checking in. The skill of directing a worker you can't supervise in real time is a fundamentally different discipline.' Tobi Lütke/Shopify on context engineering as the new critical skill. Klarna trap: excellent context engineering but missing intent framework → $40M projected savings turned into customer satisfaction crisis. Gap between chat-based prompting and autonomous agent direction is 'already 10x and compounding.' Evidence for T03 and T26.",
      "keyThemes": "Prompting taxonomy, specification engineering, intent framework building, eval harness construction, autonomous agent direction",
      "postPotential": "medium",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://natesnewsletter.substack.com/p/prompting-just-split-into-4-different"
    },
    "89": {
      "title": "Flock",
      "source": "The a16z Show",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Garrett Langley (Flock Safety CEO)",
      "date": "11 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "11 March 2026",
