        "T25"
      ],
      "summary": "Flock Safety CEO on building an AI-powered law enforcement OS — licence plate readers, drones, crime clearance at scale (million crimes/year). Notable details: drone covers 30-square-mile radius, arrives in under a minute; 12 drones sufficient for San Francisco. Constitutional tension: 24/7 drone patrol deemed analogous to the Carpenter case (warrantless search). Flock's response: only dispatch on 911 calls or active incidents, never proactive patrol. Has a 'constitutional attorney team' to review product decisions. Thriving Cities Fund: Flock deploys capital in local businesses in high-crime areas to prevent juvenile crime upstream. Indirect relevance to T25 (AI surveillance and democratic accountability) — provides a live example of an AI company navigating the surveillance cost curve in real time, with constitutional constraints as a genuine design input.",
      "keyThemes": "AI-enabled law enforcement, surveillance drones, constitutional law and surveillance, fourth amendment edge cases, licence plate readers, crime prevention technology",
      "postPotential": "medium",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/what-it-takes-to-clear-a-million-crimes-a-year-with-flock-safetys-ceo-E0aARCdV"
    },
    "90": {
      "title": "Moore",
      "source": "Big Technology Podcast (Alex Kantrowitz)",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Olivia Moore (a16z AI partner)",
      "date": "11 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T01",
        "T09",
        "T08"
      ],
      "summary": "NBC poll: AI has negative 20 net favourability — ranked below ICE, Marco Rubio, sanctuary cities. Moore: lab leaders 'not economists or consumer marketing experts' — messaging on job displacement is driving fear, not adoption. a16z Top 100 GenAI Consumer Apps: ChatGPT still 2.5–3x Gemini on web, 30x Claude. ChatGPT vs Claude app store: only 11% overlap — ChatGPT going fashion/retail/transport, Claude going premium finance/science/medicine. OpenClaw: most important architecture unlock of 2026 but not consumer-grade — flat or declining web traffic after launch spike (developers adopt, mainstream hasn't). Memory as key differentiator: '100x experience on any prior software product.' Harvard Business Review finding: AI doesn't reduce work, it intensifies it — 'I'm doing more work, not less, because I get so much leverage.' Personality test on LLMs: Claude = mild autism; Grok companion = psychosis/borderline; ChatGPT refused. Pace of change: 7 of 9 creative tools in 2023 were image generators; now only 3 remain. Strong evidence for T01 (enterprise vs consumer adoption gap), T09 (workload creep), T08 (trust/public perception).",
      "keyThemes": "AI unpopularity (57% of voters think risks outweigh benefits), consumer AI app landscape, ChatGPT vs Claude vs Gemini market positions, OpenClaw consumer adoption gap, memory as competitive moat, AI intensifies work rather than reducing it",
      "postPotential": "high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/ai-s-unpopularity-competing-with-chatgpt-with-olivia-moore"
    },
    "91": {
      "title": "Now",
      "source": "Dwarkesh Podcast (essay)",
      "host": null,
      "date": "11 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T25"
      ],
      "summary": "The most important political AI piece in the corpus. Core argument: within 20 years, the majority of the workforce in military, government, and private sector will be AI. The fight over AI governance is happening now, while stakes are manageable — better than later. Hegseth's concern is legitimate (can't become dependent on a private company with a kill switch on warfighting capability) but the government's response (supply chain risk designation) is the wrong instrument. Mass surveillance cost curve calculation: 100M CCTV cameras in America × 10 cents/million tokens × 1 frame/10 seconds = ~$30B/year today → $3B next year → $300M the year after → by 2030 it's cheaper than remodelling the White House. 'Once the technical capacity for mass surveillance exists, the only thing standing between us and an authoritarian surveillance state is the political expectation that this is not something we do here.' Government leverage: permitting for power generation, antitrust enforcement, contracts. Prediction markets: 81% chance supply chain restriction is backtracked. Essential evidence for proposed T25.",
      "keyThemes": "Anthropic-Pentagon as civilisational warning shot, AI workforce of the future, mass surveillance cost curve, democratic accountability of AI companies, private kill switches on critical infrastructure",
      "postPotential": "very-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/dow-anthropic"
    },
