    "114": {
      "title": "Peace",
      "source": "The Rachman Review (Gideon Rachman, Financial Times)",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Boris Johnson (former UK PM), interviewed in Kyiv at YES conference",
      "date": "26 February 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "tier": 2,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "Boris Johnson in Kyiv on the fourth anniversary of Russia's full-scale invasion. Core argument: the West is exerting about a tenth of the pressure needed to force Putin to negotiate; every concession emboldens him. Johnson on Trump: contain 'Trump derangement syndrome' — what Putin wants is the impression of a divided West. Europe cannot replace American military capability (70% of NATO budget, 95% heavy-lift, effectively 100% nuclear deterrent). Assets argument: €210bn of Russian money in European banks could fund Ukraine; Britain has ~£15bn in London. Symbolic European deployment ('boots on the ground not fighting') would signal resolve without escalation.",
      "keyThemes": "Ukraine-Russia war year five, transatlantic alliance fracture under Trump, Western pressure on Putin, European strategic autonomy limits, Russia frozen assets",
      "postPotential": "none",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://shows.acast.com/therachmanreview/episodes/boris-johnson-pressure-on-putin-is-the-price-of-peace"
    },
    "115": {
      "title": "Endurance",
      "source": "The Rachman Review (Gideon Rachman, Financial Times)",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Emil Hokayem (Director of Regional Security, IISS)",
      "date": "5 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "tier": 2,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "IISS analysis of the US-Israel war on Iran launched following strikes on Tehran that killed much of Iran's senior leadership. Hokayem: US and Israel have decisive military advantage but no plan for day after. Iran's strategy: use low-end drones to exhaust interceptor stockpiles before deploying more capable systems. Strait of Hormuz closure as Iran's 'asymmetric ace.' Gulf states deeply exposed — losing the 'safe haven' image is the real damage. 'Five to six weeks of intense hostilities, then a long tail.' Regime survival plus claim of not being brought to its knees = Iranian definition of success.",
      "keyThemes": "US-Israel war on Iran (Operation Epic Fury), Iran regime resilience, Strait of Hormuz threat, Gulf state exposure, battle of metrics (interceptors vs drones), no plan for day after",
      "postPotential": "none",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://shows.acast.com/therachmanreview/episodes/iran-war-risks-turning-into-a-battle-of-endurance"
    },
    "116": {
      "title": "Regime",
      "source": "The Rachman Review (Gideon Rachman, Financial Times)",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Sir Simon Gass (former British Ambassador to Iran; former Chair, UK Joint Intelligence Committee; SC Strategy)",
      "date": "12 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "tier": 2,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "Former British Ambassador to Iran on the structural resilience of the Iranian system. Key intelligence insight: 'Anyone who's studied Iran would not have expected decapitation strikes to work — the system is built on defiance and survival.' New Supreme Leader Mottabar Khamenei is a hardliner; succession happened under war conditions, almost inevitably producing a hardliner. The IRGC is the actual power centre. Nuclear angle: Iran has consistently been a threshold nuclear state (maintaining capability without weaponising) — the fatwa against nuclear weapons lapsed on Khamenei's death; now under existential pressure, some voices will push for full weaponisation. Gass: the 2015 JCPOA nuclear deal was working; Trump withdrew in 2018 and the current war was not inevitable. Strait of Hormuz: Iran needs only to deter shipowners, not physically close the strait. Gulf states are angry at both Iran and Israel/US; the value of the US security guarantee is now openly questioned.",
      "keyThemes": "Iran's new Supreme Leader (Mottabar Khamenei), IRGC as dominant power centre, regime resilience post-decapitation, nuclear proliferation stakes, Gulf state anger at both Iran and US, UK strategic choice on war participation, Strait of Hormuz, Russian nuclear deterrence precedent",
      "postPotential": "medium",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://shows.acast.com/therachmanreview/episodes/formidable-us-firepower-fails-to-unseat-irans-regime"
    },
