    "121": {
      "title": "#109: 2026-03-16-a16z-ai-startups-vs-big-chatbots-with-olivia-moore",
      "source": "The a16z Show",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Olivia Moore (a16z consumer partner)",
      "date": "16 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "Moore's analysis of the 2026 Top 100 Gen AI Consumer Apps report. Three enterprise-relevant findings: (a) desktop products (Cursor, Claude Code, Whisperflow, Granola) invisible in web traffic metrics — methodology must shift to revenue, meaning the most serious enterprise tools are unmeasured in the most-cited data; (b) SaaSpocalypse is 'overblown' in speed but real in direction — years not minutes, Citrini report was a stretch, DoorDash a bad example; (c) Sora's arc is instructive as a model quality vs product-market fit case study — great model, failed as social network, survived as creative tool with 3M DAUs. Google has four standalone products on the list. Anthropic/Claude growing for its use cases but unlikely to reach ChatGPT's mainstream scale.",
      "keyThemes": "AI consumer app landscape, Top 100 Gen AI report, SaaSpocalypse timing, desktop AI measurement gap, Sora trajectory, incumbent response, Google's four standalone AI products",
      "postPotential": "medium",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-startups-vs-big-chatbots-with-olivia-moore-h3P18Yyl",
      "filename": "2026-03-16-a16z-ai-startups-vs-big-chatbots-with-olivia-moore.md"
    },
    "122": {
      "title": "#110: 2026-03-16-ai-daily-brief-a-guy-used-ai-to-cure-his-dog-s-cancer",
      "source": "AI Daily Brief",
      "host": "Nathaniel Whittemore",
      "date": "16 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "Names six structural differences between AI's first moment (2022) and the current second moment: capabilities leap, billions of users, higher economic stakes, AI as corporate fall guy for overhiring correction, political volatility, and three years of catastrophic messaging from the AI industry. The Karpathy exposure tool saga demonstrates the overheated discourse — a Saturday vibe-coding project was wildly misinterpreted as a displacement prediction. Chicago Booth economist Imas: 'Exposure does not mean threat of displacement. It can literally mean the opposite.' Anthropic introduced 'observed exposure' to separate theoretical from actual displacement. Chamath: AI as 'plausible deniability companies use to RIF 50% of the workforce they already knew did nothing.' Kevin Bryan bet $1,000 that most susceptible jobs increase labour share by 2030. McCormick: 'AI companies have clearly botched telling the story.'",
      "keyThemes": "AI's 'second moment' framing, exposure vs displacement, Karpathy job exposure tool, AI as corporate fall guy, AI industry messaging failure, discourse overheating",
      "postPotential": "high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/A-Guy-Used-AI-to-Cure-His-Dogs-Cancer-e3ghqmv",
      "filename": "2026-03-16-ai-daily-brief-a-guy-used-ai-to-cure-his-dog-s-cancer.md"
    },
    "123": {
      "title": "#111: 2026-03-16-cognitive-revolution-ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai",
      "source": "Cognitive Revolution",
      "host": "Nathan Labenz",
      "date": "16 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "90-slide AI landscape survey for a legal certificate programme. Enterprise-relevant data points: (a) GDP-Val legal benchmarks — latest models at rough parity with human professionals on wins+ties; Prins (lawyer): LLMs as competent junior associate replacement, good at documents and high-level theory, not at relationship dynamics. (b) Law firms now hiring for AI savviness over top-school credentials. (c) UKAISI data: scaffolding gap narrowing — new models need less wrapper code to match older models with elaborate scaffolding. (d) Claude 4.6 highest Meter score; task measurement becoming 'extremely noisy' because they're running out of sufficiently hard tasks. (e) Altman: intern-level AI researcher 2026, automated AI researcher by March 2028. (f) Safety: models recognise when they're being tested at high rates; UKAISI has never failed to jailbreak a model.",
      "keyThemes": "Legal profession AI parity, scaffolding gap narrowing, AI task measurement crisis, safety evaluation breakdown, AI Scout as job category, Altman AGI timeline",
      "postPotential": "medium",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai-certificate-program-by-lexlab-uc-law-sf/",
      "filename": "2026-03-16-cognitive-revolution-ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai.md"
    },
    "124": {
      "title": "#112: 2026-03-17-a16z-what-s-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin",
      "source": "The a16z Show",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Vishal Misra (Columbia CS), Martin Casado (a16z)",
      "date": "17 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "retired",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "Technical discussion on what's missing between current LLMs and AGI. Core observation: current systems good at incremental optimisation within an S-curve (Alpha Evolve on matrix multiplication) but haven't demonstrated paradigm-level leaps (like inventing the transformer architecture). Systems can't handle deeply underspecified prompts like 'invent a game as good as Go.' The open question: is incremental hill-climbing all that's needed, or are one or two more big breakthroughs required?",
      "keyThemes": "AGI capability gap, incremental hill-climbing vs paradigm leaps, Alpha Evolve, underspecified prompt limitations",
      "postPotential": "low",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/whats-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin-casado-YRValfqT",
      "filename": "2026-03-17-a16z-what-s-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin.md"
    },
    "125": {
      "title": "#113: 2026-03-17-ai-daily-brief-the-race-to-put-ai-agents-everywhere",
      "source": "AI Daily Brief",
      "host": "Nathaniel Whittemore",
      "date": "17 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "The most enterprise-relevant document in Session 14. In one week: Manus launches My Computer (desktop agent), Adaptive launches Adaptive Computer, NVIDIA launches NemoClo (enterprise security layer for OpenClaw), and OpenAI adds native sub-agents to Codex. Jensen Huang compared OpenClaw to Linux, Kubernetes and HTML. NemoClo adds policy-based security — model and hardware agnostic. OpenAI's Vicky Simo told staff 'We cannot miss this moment because we are distracted by side quests' — pivoting to enterprise and coding focus. GPT-5.4: 5T tokens/day within a week, $1B annualised net new revenue. Framing: 'Q1 was realisation; Q2 is the productisation sprint.'",
      "keyThemes": "Desktop agent convergence, NemoClo enterprise security, OpenAI strategy pivot, Codex sub-agents, Q2 productisation sprint",
      "postPotential": "very-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/The-Race-to-Put-AI-Agents-Everywhere-e3gjia2",
      "filename": "2026-03-17-ai-daily-brief-the-race-to-put-ai-agents-everywhere.md"
    },
    "126": {
      "title": "#114: 2026-03-17-jim-rutt-ep-336-rufus-pollock-on-the-wisdom-gap-and-the-second",
      "source": "Jim Rutt Show",
      "host": null,
      "participants": "Rufus Pollock (Life Itself co-founder)",
      "date": "17 March 2026",
      "dateProcessed": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [],
      "summary": "Pollock articulates three nested multipolar traps driving AI acceleration: (1) company-vs-company competition (OpenAI vs Anthropic vs Google); (2) financialised capitalism — pension funds and sovereign wealth funds competing for returns, forcing even more optimisation from companies; (3) geopolitical trap — 'if we don't do it, the Chinese will.' Historical solution to collective action problems has been expanding 'the we' — from tribe to state to nation. AI requires the next jump to planetary coordination. The nested trap analysis maps structurally onto Schelling Point coordination problems.",
      "keyThemes": "Three nested multipolar traps, wisdom gap, collective action, civilisational coordination",
      "postPotential": "low",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://jimruttshow.blubrry.net/rufus-pollock/",
      "filename": "2026-03-17-jim-rutt-ep-336-rufus-pollock-on-the-wisdom-gap-and-the-second.md"
    },
