    "150": {
      "title": "What's Missing Between LLMs and AGI",
      "source": "The a16z Show",
      "host": "Martin Casado",
      "participants": "Vishal Misra",
      "date": "2026-03-17",
      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-23",
      "session": 20,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T03",
        "T05",
        "T06"
      ],
      "summary": "A conversation between Casado and Misra (Columbia CS professor) probing the gap between current LLM capabilities and AGI — specifically whether recursive self-improvement systems like Alpha Evolve represent a path to AGI or merely incremental hill-climbing on an existing S-curve. The episode's analytical contribution is a clean distinction between two modes of AI progress: incremental optimisation (faster matrix multiplication, code refinement) where current systems excel, and conjectural leaps (inventing a new architecture like transformers, or 'invent a game as good as go') where current systems fail because the problem is too unconstrained. Misra's framing — 'we have systems that do the hill climbing of the S-curve that you're currently on' but not systems that jump between S-curves — has direct implications for enterprise AI strategy: organisations planning around continuous capability improvement may be correct for the near term, but the next discontinuity (if it comes) will invalidate plans built on extrapolation.",
      "keyThemes": "Incremental vs conjectural AI progress, recursive self-improvement constraints, Alpha Evolve as bounded optimisation, hard takeoff vs gradual improvement, underspecified prompts as capability boundary",
      "postPotential": "medium",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "filename": "2026-03-17-a16z-what-s-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin.md",
      "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/whats-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin-casado-YRValfqT"
    },
