      ],
      "summary": "A policy interview with the US Undersecretary of State for Economic Affairs laying out the administration's three-front strategy to win the AI race: model quality superiority, global market share, and secure supply chains. The episode's analytical contribution is narrow but specific: it articulates the official US government framing of AI as an industrial policy instrument — compute and minerals as the 21st-century equivalent of oil and steel — and provides the clearest statement yet of the 'secular growth acceleration' thesis from inside government (GDP growth breaking 5%, productivity breaking 5%, economy characterised as supply-constrained). For the corpus, this is ambient geopolitical context rather than enterprise AI content, but the supply chain fragility argument and the re-industrialisation framing have peripheral relevance to how regulated enterprises think about AI infrastructure dependencies.",
      "keyThemes": "US AI industrial policy, supply chain security as AI prerequisite, secular growth acceleration thesis, compute-as-oil framing, Middle East as AI energy partner, tariffs as re-industrialisation mechanism, model distillation as IP threat",
      "postPotential": "low",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/jacob-helberg-draft-6EvVv6rO"
    },
    "156": {
      "title": "Understanding Consumer Debt Collections: The Underbelly of Finance",
      "source": "Complex Systems with Patrick McKenzie (patio11)",
      "host": "Patrick McKenzie",
      "participants": "None (solo essay reading with live commentary)",
      "filename": "2026-03-19-complex-systems-with-patrick-mckenzie-understanding-consumer-debt-collections-the-underbelly-of.md",
      "date": "2026-03-19",
      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-23",
      "session": 22,
      "tier": 2,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T08"
      ],
      "summary": "A detailed structural anatomy of the US consumer debt collection industry, originally published as a Bits About Money essay in August 2023 and read with live commentary. The episode's analytical contribution to the corpus is narrow but specific: it provides the clearest case study yet of how complex systems produce systematically harmful outcomes without any single actor intending harm — a pattern McKenzie traces through CSV-file-mediated information loss, incentive misalignment between issuers and collectors, labour economics that ensure incompetent and abusive collection practices, and a legal system that functions as consensual social fiction. The 'litigious debtor scrub' — where databases of people who know their rights are compiled so collectors can avoid them and concentrate abuse on those who don't — is a striking example of how technological efficiency can be deployed to circumvent rather than comply with regulation. For the corpus, this is ambient infrastructure context rather than enterprise AI content, but the structural patterns — legibility failures, incentive-driven system dysfunction, the gap between regulatory intent and operational reality — have peripheral relevance to how AI systems will interact with existing institutional infrastructure in regulated industries.",
      "keyThemes": "Structural system dysfunction without individual malice, legibility failures in data-mediated processes, regulatory intent vs operational reality gap, labour economics driving quality collapse, information loss through institutional interfaces",
      "postPotential": "low",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://www.complexsystemspodcast.com/debt-collections/"
    },
    "157": {
      "title": "Why I Changed My Mind About Apple — Apple as AI's Hardware Winner",
      "source": "Exponential View Newsletter",
      "host": "Azeem Azhar",
      "filename": "2026-03-19-ev-newsletter-why-i-changed-my-mind-about-apple.md",
      "date": "2026-03-19",
      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-23",
      "session": 22,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T05",
        "T23",
        "T07",
        "T01"
      ],
      "summary": "Azhar articulates a thesis that Apple's AI strategy is not about building models but about controlling the device layer through which all models are accessed — unified memory architecture, Neural Engine, privacy enclave, and App Store capture. The analytical contribution is the '4K ceiling' concept: most daily AI tasks don't require frontier intelligence, and through distillation, GPT-5.8-level capability is arriving on local devices, shifting the competitive question from 'which model?' to 'whose device?' This reframes the AI value chain for enterprise planners — the assumption that model quality is the durable competitive axis may be wrong for the majority of use cases.",
      "keyThemes": "4K ceiling thesis, device-layer value capture, local inference demand, unified memory as AI infrastructure, Apple as accidental AI hardware company, model distillation shifting competitive axis",
      "postPotential": "medium-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "The 4K ceiling concept is a clean, memorable framework that reframes enterprise AI strategy away from model selection toward infrastructure and platform dependency. The Best Buy shelf-clearing anecdote is vivid and concrete. The enterprise extrapolation — a company of 100,000 needing 25,000 new machines — is the kind of number that makes senior leaders sit up. However, much of this evidence was already partially captured in Session 1 from the same source. The post potential is in the crystallised 4K ceiling framework itself, which is now more fully articulated than in previous captures.",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/why-i-changed-my-mind-about-apple"
    },
    "158": {
      "title": "Andrej Karpathy on Code Agents, AutoResearch, and the Loopy Era of AI",
      "source": "No Priors",
      "host": "No Priors hosts",
      "participants": "Andrej Karpathy",
      "filename": "2026-03-20-no-priors-andrej-karpathy-on-code-agents-autoresearch-and-the-loopy.md",
      "date": "2026-03-20",
      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-23",
      "session": 22,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T03",
        "T01"
      ],
      "summary": "Karpathy pushes back on the 'year of agents' narrative from the labs, arguing the correct framing is 'decade of agents' — a timeline calibrated by 15 years of watching AI predictions overshoot. The analytical contribution is narrow but specific: Karpathy names the concrete capability gaps (continual learning, multimodality, computer use, cognitive depth) that prevent current agents from functioning as the 'intern or employee' metaphor implies, and frames these as tractable but difficult problems requiring years of engineering, not months. For enterprise audiences, the signal is that the most credible practitioner voice in the field is explicitly warning against the productisation sprint timeline that labs are selling.",
      "keyThemes": "Decade-not-year agent timeline, agent capability gaps as engineering problems, continual learning as missing primitive, overprediction correction from practitioner experience",
      "postPotential": "medium-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "Karpathy is arguably the most credible individual voice in AI engineering. His explicit pushback on the labs' 'year of agents' framing — from someone who built and used these tools at the frontier — directly contradicts the Q2 2026 productisation sprint narrative already in the corpus (AI Daily Brief, 17 March). The tension between what labs are selling and what a practitioner says actually works is precisely the enterprise diffusion gap story. The 'decade not year' framing is clean, quotable, and immediately useful for enterprise leaders being pressured to move faster than the technology warrants.",
      "_reconstructed": false,
      "url": "https://www.youtube.com/@NoPriorsPodcast/search?query=Andrej%20Karpathy%20on%20Code%20Agents%2C%20AutoResearch%2C%20and%20the%20Loopy%20"
    },
