    "170": {
      "title": "Rufus Pollock on the Wisdom Gap and the Second Renaissance",
      "source": "Jim Rutt Show",
      "host": "Jim Rutt",
      "participants": "Rufus Pollock (Life Itself, Open Knowledge Foundation)",
      "filename": "2026-03-17-jim-rutt-ep-336-rufus-pollock-on-the-wisdom-gap-and-the-second.md",
      "url": "https://jimruttshow.blubrry.net/rufus-pollock/",
      "date": "2026-03-17",
      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-24",
      "session": 29,
      "tier": 2,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T08",
        "T21"
      ],
      "summary": "Pollock argues that the information age has failed to deliver wisdom — more data and accessibility hasn't produced better collective decision-making. His 'Second Renaissance' thesis posits that we need a civilisational shift from information abundance to wisdom cultivation. This maps to the AI era: AI amplifies information abundance but doesn't automatically produce wisdom. The gap between AI capability and organisational wisdom is the enterprise version of Pollock's civilisational wisdom gap.",
      "keyThemes": "wisdom gap, information abundance vs wisdom, Second Renaissance, civilisational meta-narrative, technology-culture mismatch",
      "postPotential": "medium",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "The wisdom gap framing could work as a contrarian angle: enterprises are investing in AI capability (more information processing) while the bottleneck is wisdom (knowing what to do with it). But needs more enterprise-specific grounding."
    },
