      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T01",
        "T04",
        "T05",
        "T08",
        "T10",
        "T28"
      ],
      "summary": "Sankar argues the AI value stack concentrates at two layers — chips and 'ontology' (structured data infrastructure) — not at the model layer. The 1989-to-present defence stat is the anchor: specialist defence spending went from 6% to 86% of major weapon systems, destroying the dual-use industrial base that won WW2. His thesis: the current AI moment is a chance to reverse this by rebuilding the civil-military bridge, and the enterprise analogy holds — companies that invest in data infrastructure rather than chasing model capability will accumulate durable value.",
      "keyThemes": "Ontology over models, forward-deployed engineering, defence-to-commercial transfer, vibe coding as enterprise threat, US industrial mobilisation deficit",
      "postPotential": "high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "Sankar's 'ontology' thesis directly contradicts the model-centric AI narrative. The 6% → 86% defence stat is a powerful data point. The forward-deployed engineering model is a concrete example of how enterprises should think about AI deployment — embed it in operations, don't build it in isolation.",
      "_reconstructed": false
    },
    "177": {
      "title": "Product Convergence: Why Every AI Company Is Building the Same Thing",
      "source": "AI Daily Brief",
      "host": "Nathaniel Whittemore",
      "participants": "",
      "filename": "2026-03-20-ai-daily-brief-every-ai-product-is-becoming-every-other-ai-product.md",
