    "178": {
      "title": "The 80/20 Problem: Terence Tao on Why AI Solves the Easy Part of Science",
      "source": "Dwarkesh Podcast",
      "host": "Dwarkesh Patel",
      "participants": "Terence Tao (Fields Medal mathematician)",
      "filename": "2026-03-20-dwarkesh-terence-tao-kepler-newton-and-the-true-nature-of.md",
      "url": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/terence-tao",
      "date": "2026-03-20",
      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-24",
      "session": 34,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T06",
        "T08",
        "T21",
        "T29"
      ],
      "summary": "Tao frames AI's scientific capability through the Kepler analogy: LLMs can do what Kepler did (try thousands of hypothetical relationships against data) but not what Newton did (construct a unifying theory that explains why). AI excels at breadth — 'we have to redesign the way we do science to take full advantage of this breadth capability' — but on depth, Tao reports 5x productivity on auxiliary tasks with zero speedup on core mathematical work. The 80/20 split is structural: existing methods solve 80%, but top journals publish the 20% requiring new conceptual constructions. On any given hard problem, AI tools have 'a success rate of maybe 1% or 2%' — the cherry-picked wins mask systematic limitations.",
      "keyThemes": "80/20 capability split, breadth-vs-depth complementarity, 5x auxiliary / 0x core productivity, 1-2% systematic success rate vs cherry-picked wins, Lean formal verification, serendipity destruction risk",
      "postPotential": "very-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "Tao's 80/20 framing is immediately transferable to enterprise AI adoption — every organisation faces the same problem (AI handles routine work but can't do the creative synthesis that creates competitive advantage). The Kepler-as-LLM analogy is memorable and quotable. The proof verification backdoor finding connects to T29 (safety testing collapse).",
      "_reconstructed": false
    },
