      ],
      "summary": "Azhar argues the AI debate is measuring the wrong curve — capability (are models improving?) instead of diffusion (are people using them at scale?). His internal combustion engine analogy: a Ferrari engine on your lawn is less valuable than a ten-year-old engine in a car you can drive. OpenClaw is the 'harness' that crossed the 'leave it to its own devices' threshold. His personal token consumption: 150k/day in summer 2024 → 100m/day two weeks ago → 870m in a single day this week. The inference economics: Groq + Vera Rubin delivers 35x throughput per megawatt vs Blackwell. His warning to enterprises: treating token budgets as IT cost centres is 'the equivalent of requiring engineers to book time on the engine through the facilities department.'",
