    "183": {
      "title": "The AI Layoff Theatre: Why Companies Exaggerate AI Job Replacement",
      "source": "AI Daily Brief",
      "host": "Nathaniel Whittemore",
      "participants": "",
      "filename": "2026-03-22-ai-daily-brief-why-ai-actually-won-t-take-your-job.md",
      "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Why-AI-Actually-Wont-Take-Your-Job-e3gq5op",
      "date": "2026-03-22",
      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-24",
      "session": 34,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T10",
        "T21",
        "T27"
      ],
      "summary": "Whittemore dismantles the 'AI will replace all jobs' narrative with a resume.org survey of 1,000 hiring managers: 60% said they emphasised AI's role in layoffs because it's 'viewed more favourably by stakeholders' — yet only 9% said AI had actually replaced any roles. The gap between narrative and reality is structural: markets reward 'proactive restructuring' framing and punish 'we overhired' accountability. Whittemore's own framework — 'efficiency AI' (doing the same with fewer people) vs 'opportunity AI' (doing new things that weren't possible) — is the decision frame. Jensen's related point: 'For companies with imagination, you will do more with more.'",
      "keyThemes": "AI layoff theatre (60% exaggerate, 9% real), efficiency AI vs opportunity AI, human preference as market force, corporate responsibility in AI transition, historical precedent for technological job fears",
      "postPotential": "very-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "The 60%/9% stat is a killer data point — immediately challenges the dominant narrative. The 'efficiency AI vs opportunity AI' framework from Jensen gives enterprise leaders a concrete decision framework. This episode provides the contrarian angle Scott's audience needs: the fear is real but the evidence doesn't support it at the claimed scale.",
      "_reconstructed": false
    },
