      "summary": "Vaidya describes how Composio solved the agent integration problem: 50,000+ tools across 1,000+ apps, all delivered as a single MCP server. The key innovation is the self-improving layer — the system learns from agent failures and guides future tool usage, making agents 'take a straight path' on repeat tasks. Labenz identifies the enterprise angle: MCP gives 'observability, traceability — and for that reason, better for enterprise use cases' versus CLI alternatives. Progressive disclosure — giving agents only the tools they need for each task — is the design principle that scales.",
      "keyThemes": "Single MCP server for 1000+ apps, self-improving tool guidance, progressive disclosure for agents, MCP vs CLI for enterprise observability, agent tool discovery",
      "postPotential": "medium-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "The 'one MCP server for everything' pattern is a concrete architectural insight. The self-improving tool layer connects to T26 (agentic loops) — agents that get better at using tools through experience. Enterprise angle: MCP for observability/traceability is directly relevant to regulated industries.",
