      "dateProcessed": "2026-03-25",
      "session": 35,
      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T28",
        "T34"
      ],
      "summary": "Maier reveals a concrete bottleneck in military AI adoption: the US military's power infrastructure can't support the electronic battlefield it's building. A soldier draws 30-60 watts continuously; add drones, sensors, edge AI, and autonomous systems and the 15kW diesel generator — running at 500 watts 99% of the time — becomes both insufficient and a detectable signature. Chariot's thesis is that commercial EV and eVTOL breakthroughs have already solved 80% of this at the cell and module level, and a defence startup can bridge the remaining 20% (ruggedisation, thermal management, silent operation) faster than traditional defence primes. The 'coffee pot taking down air defence radar' anecdote captures the fragility of current military power infrastructure.",
      "keyThemes": "Tactical power as AI bottleneck, commercial-to-military technology transfer, 80/20 commercial solution thesis, electronic battlefield energy demands, defence procurement reform",
      "postPotential": "medium-high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "The 'coffee pot vs air defence radar' story is vivid and memorable. The 80/20 commercial-military thesis mirrors Sankar's ontology argument — the hard part isn't the technology, it's the operational integration. Enterprise leaders in regulated industries face the same pattern: commercial AI solves 80%, the last 20% requires domain-specific engineering.",
      "_reconstructed": false
    },
