      "tier": 1,
      "status": "active",
      "themes": [
        "T03",
        "T14",
        "T28"
      ],
      "summary": "Pandey proposes two new layers (L8 syntactic, L9 semantic) on top of the OSI networking stack to enable what he calls the 'Internet of Cognition' — infrastructure for agents to share context, understand intent, and coordinate without centralised control. Cisco's internal CAIPE system (20 agents handling 10+ workflows for observability, orchestration, networking, and security — reducing team load by 30%, with 40% of tasks handled end-to-end) demonstrates multi-agent SRE at production scale, though the IoC layers (shared cognition, intent alignment) are not yet implemented in CAIPE. Labenz frames the distributed approach as a structural safety argument: 'the distributed nature of this system makes it extremely difficult and rare for any individual to accumulate a systemically dangerous amount of power' — in direct contrast to the scaling-up paradigm of frontier labs.",
      "keyThemes": "Internet of Cognition (L8/L9 layers), CAIPE 20-agent system, MCP + A2A protocol integration, latent space transfer protocol, distributed vs concentrated AI power, minimum-permission agent paradigm",
      "postPotential": "high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "Pandey's L8/L9 proposal is the most concrete architectural vision for enterprise agent infrastructure. The minimum-permission paradigm gives security teams something specific to evaluate. The distributed-vs-concentrated framing connects AI safety to enterprise architecture in a way that hasn't been articulated elsewhere.",
      "_reconstructed": false
    },
