        "T39"
      ],
      "summary": "Cape CEO John Doyle and Navy CTO Justin Finelli frame Salt Typhoon — China's confirmed infiltration of major US telcos via lawful intercept X1 interfaces — as a case study in the failure of perimeter security thinking: Doyle's SRE team found an installer from a lawful intercept vendor containing an unencrypted text file with credentials for every client of that vendor, three months before Salt Typhoon broke publicly. Cape's response — a 'clean install' MVNO running encrypted software on assumed-hostile physical infrastructure, piloted on Guam ahead of schedule and under budget — articulates an assume-hostile architecture principle with direct enterprise implications. The episode also documents Navy acquisition transformation: from 4 to 168 defence-tech VCs in seven years (42X), from 2 to 25 pilots annually, with programme managers trained to close in 3 months rather than 18.",
      "keyThemes": "Salt Typhoon / lawful intercept compromise, assume-hostile architecture, MVNO as clean-install infrastructure, CALEA vendor credentials incident, Navy acquisition reform (4→168 VCs, 2→25 pilots), defence-commercial dual-use model, unclassified shareable tech evaluations as trust infrastructure",
      "postPotential": "high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "The CALEA vendor credentials story is the most concrete, verifiable supply-chain security failure in the corpus — specific, shocking, and directly applicable to enterprise software procurement. The assume-hostile architecture principle generalises from telecoms to enterprise AI infrastructure. The Navy acquisition reform numbers (42X VC growth, 3-month vs 18-month deals) are usable as direct evidence for the enterprise AI diffusion gap.",
      "_reconstructed": false
    },
