      "summary": "Liam Byrne's book-tour conversation at Intelligence Squared maps the political economy of authoritarian populism: funded (£173 million into UK right-wing media and political infrastructure over five years, per Byrne's analysis of Electoral Commission, Companies House, and parliamentary register of interests data), and algorithmically amplified via social media's outrage logic. Byrne identifies three separate forces that could push the West past populism's tipping point: 'the great disillusion' worsened by AI; social media division; and migration pressure from 1.2 billion people entering global labour markets over the next decade to 15 years against perhaps 400-600 million available jobs. Editorial inference: for regulated-industry enterprise leaders, this frames AI deployment within a macro political stability context — AI is explicitly identified by a senior UK politician as a force intensifying the economic grievances that are reshaping the political environment.",
