      "summary": "Rosedale's 20-year experiment building Second Life provides empirical grounding for a core insight: network topology determines culture more profoundly than rules or moderation. Local membranes prevent power-law domination by bad actors; open fields amplify them. Host Jim Rutt extends this to AI agents — predicting the statistically most common instruction given to personal AI assistants will be 'go hustle people for money and stay anonymous,' a warning he has held for three to four years. Both converge on the personal agent ownership problem: an agent you pay for directly serves you; a platform agent serves the platform.",
      "keyThemes": "Social topology as cultural architecture, personal agent ownership and alignment, crypto-to-AI warning, anonymity-then-identity design, emergent complexity from simple rules, consciousness as world-model introspection",
      "postPotential": "high",
      "postPotentialReasoning": "Three distinct enterprise-relevant angles: (1) crypto warning for AI agents — timely and provocative; (2) agent business model as trust signal — quiet observation; (3) social topology as governance design principle — educational/architectural. Rosedale's 20-year empirical base makes each defensible."
    },
