        {
          "session": 15,
          "source": "Azhar Soul.md (EV Podcast, Feb 2026)",
          "content": "12KB personality spec. 179 corrections in first 10 days. 146 behavioural patterns extracted. Big Five profile: Conscientiousness 5/5, Openness 4/5.",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/building-with-agents"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief (18 March)",
          "content": "Capability uplift vs encoded preference — two-category framework for agent skills. Capability uplift skills help the model do things it can't do natively and depreciate as models improve. Encoded preference skills sequence things the model already can do according to your team's workflow — durable but only as good as their fidelity to actual workflow. The distinction matters for testing: different failure modes for each category.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-to-Use-Agent-Skills-e3glb09"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution/Zvi (19 March)",
          "content": "The real productivity gain from AI tools isn't in the output quality — it's in the preserved flow state. Chrome extension for workflow automation saves ~1hr/day directly, but the bigger value is eliminating context-switching into logistics. This maps to a skill that's invisible in most productivity analyses.",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/zvi-s-mic-works-recursive-self-improvement-live-player-analysis-anthropic-vs-dow-more/"
        },
        {
          "session": 17,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Coolest Agents (14 March 2026)",
          "content": "Whittemore describes vibe-coding as the prototyping method for all 16 agents: 'all vibe-coded or AI-assisted builds.' The Chucky agent surfaces a new professional challenge: how do you demonstrate agent-building competency? 'A resume isn't going to do it, nor is any sort of traditional cover letter. And even a portfolio approach kind of falls down because you can't just drop a screenshot and say good enough.' Solution: an agent that acts as the builder's representative — the portfolio is itself an agent. The skill demonstration problem for agentic engineering is structurally different from traditional software engineering portfolios.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/The-Coolest-Agents-Ive-Built-So-Far-e3geoup"
        },
        {
          "session": 33,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - How to Use Agent Skills (2026-03-18)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-to-Use-Agent-Skills-e3gp0v5",
          "content": "Agent skills as the new engineering discipline: defining capabilities, setting boundaries, composing workflows. Whittemore walks through practical configuration — this is the operational reality of 'agentic engineering' beyond the hype."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z - Sankar/Palantir (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Sankar on operational context as the skill: 'The most compelling AI applications I'm seeing across commercial or public sector are being built by people who deeply understand the operational context.' His 'iron man suit' metaphor: AI should augment operators, not replace them. 'I'm not sure why the goal is replacing people to begin with.' The skill is embedding AI into existing workflows — what he calls building on the 'ontology' layer.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/inside-palantir-building-software-that-matters-with-shyam-sankar-mSRYC1eQ"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution - Composio (22 Mar)",
          "content": "Labenz on progressive disclosure: 'whether it's an MCP or a CLI, you can probably do progressive disclosure and avoid crazy bloat if you think about things the right way.' Vaidya on self-improving tools: 'We also learn from failures — dos and don'ts for using particular tools, use cases, pitfalls.' The tools adapt through usage — 'the next time agent does something similar, it will take a straight path, making it more reliable, robust and token efficient.'",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/your-agent-s-self-improving-swiss-army-knife-composio-cto-karan-vaidya-on-building-smart-tools/"
        },
        {
          "session": 47,
          "source": "Exponential View Podcast - Solving Problems with the Karpathy Loop (2026-03-27)",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/solving-problems-with-the-karpathy",
          "content": "Azhar describes the design skills required for effective agentic loops: constructing oracle panels ('three or four judges that are synthetic judges that would judge that on three specific criteria'), designing escape harnesses to escape local minima (random perturbation), and setting stopping criteria ('I tend to have this thing stop at 20 iterations'). The act of defining the objective function is itself valuable: 'That in of itself is a very, very useful piece of self-reflection to help me think about the problem to hand.'"
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
