    "T05": {
      "name": "Knowledge Work Commoditisation",
      "created": "Session 11",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 47",
      "documentCount": 30,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "Moore/a16z (16 March)",
          "content": "SaaSpocalypse 'a bit overblown' — AI-native companies will eat incumbents, but in years not minutes. Citrini report was overblown. DoorDash was a bad example. Incumbents fighting back — Google has four standalone AI products on Top 100.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-startups-vs-big-chatbots-with-olivia-moore-h3P18Yyl"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "Moonshots Abundance Summit (17 March)",
          "content": "Apple unified memory as massive compute overhang — M5 neural cores massively underutilised. 'Biggest waste of silicon in the history of the world.' Nobody building native Mac AI apps that exploit the capability. 'That overhang — I would be surprised if it doesn't collapse in the next year.'",
          "url": "https://www.youtube.com/@PeterDiamandis/search?query=Meta%20Buys%20Moltbook%2C%20GPT%205.4%2C%20and%20Fruitfly%20Brain%20Upload%20%7C%20Moo"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution/Zvi (19 March)",
          "content": "Lab competition thinning to Big Three. xAI disqualified by talent acquisition failure. Meta should license rather than build. Google in danger of falling from top tier — not a model quality claim but a scaffolding, integration, and culture claim. Gemini models 'deeply psychologically screwed up and paranoid.' Corporate culture 'fundamentally broken.' No serious coding agent. Critical: recursive self-improvement gap will compound.",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/zvi-s-mic-works-recursive-self-improvement-live-player-analysis-anthropic-vs-dow-more/"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "EV Newsletter/Azhar (19 March)",
          "content": "Apple as platform winner through device-layer capture. The 4K ceiling thesis: most daily tasks don't need frontier intelligence; GPT-5.8-level capability arriving on local devices through distillation. 'When local is good enough for the task, the question is no longer which model but whose device?' Apple captures value at the device layer regardless of which model wins. On track to surpass $1B AI revenue in 2026.",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/why-i-changed-my-mind-about-apple"
        },
        {
          "session": 20,
          "source": "The a16z Show - Misra & Casado (17 March 2026)",
          "content": "Misra frames current AI capability as strong at constrained optimisation but weak at open-ended problem formulation. 'They're good if you give them very specific instructions about what you're trying to do. But if you give them a very vague high-level instruction, that wouldn't work currently.' This maps to the commoditisation thesis: the tasks AI commoditises fastest are well-specified, constrained optimisation problems — precisely the knowledge work that can be fully described in a prompt. Work that requires problem formulation, ambiguity navigation, and conjectural reasoning remains resistant.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/whats-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin-casado-YRValfqT"
        },
        {
          "session": 22,
          "source": "Exponential View Newsletter - Why I Changed My Mind About Apple (19 March 2026)",
          "content": "Azhar's 4K ceiling thesis fully articulated: 'When television manufacturers hit 4K resolution, a few pushed further. 8K sets appeared in showrooms, some people bought them. But the human eye can't resolve detail above roughly 4K at normal viewing distances and the industry found its natural ceiling. No one is seriously building 16K TVs. I think AI is approaching the same thing — not at the frontier, but for the tasks that actually fill most people's days.' The implication for commoditisation: 'For most daily tasks, you don't need GPT-19.6. You need something closer to GPT-5.8 and through model distillation and efficiency improvements, that level of capability is already arriving on local devices.' This means model quality commoditises faster than expected for the majority of enterprise use cases — frontier capability matters for drug discovery and hard reasoning, but most knowledge work hits a sufficiency ceiling well below the frontier.",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/why-i-changed-my-mind-about-apple"
        },
        {
          "session": 24,
          "source": "The a16z Show - AI Startups vs Big Chatbots (16 Mar 2026)",
          "content": "Image generation as the canary: standalone startups absorbed by ChatGPT and Gemini overnight. Any feature-level AI capability gets commoditised once platforms decide to build it. Only workflow-level or vertical-level companies survive.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-startups-vs-big-chatbots-with-olivia-moore-h3P18Yyl"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z - Sankar/Palantir (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Sankar's rubric for vibe coding's enterprise impact: 'What software is really fundamentally about beta and what software is about alpha.' Beta software (commodity functions) gets disrupted by vibe coding. Alpha software (domain-specific, workflow-embedded) survives because the switching costs aren't technical — they're operational. 'You're not going to vibe code Atlassian' but you might vibe code the internal tool that nobody maintains.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/inside-palantir-building-software-that-matters-with-shyam-sankar-mSRYC1eQ"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Convergence (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Lovable's ARR jumped from $300m to $400m in a single month — while expanding from code-only to general tasks. 71.3% of respondents were vibe coding in February. Whittemore: 'thinking about vibe coding as its own category might be increasingly reductive' — code generation is becoming the substrate for all AI-powered knowledge work, not a standalone category.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Every-AI-Product-Is-Becoming-Every-Other-AI-Product-e3goh0v"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z Podcast - AI Just Gave You Superpowers (19 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-just-gave-you-superpowers-now-what-w1BZEEnu",
          "content": "Catalini's paper frames measurability as the fundamental divide: 'anything that can be measured will be automated.' For software engineering: 'just kind of writing the code is plummeting' while verification becomes primary — 'making sure the code works...that it provides value for the customer as they need it or it serves business goals.' Lazarin: engineers 'weren't just printing the code. They were doing this work too' — the iterative process of 'correcting and straightening and feedback gathering.' In 'vibe coding extreme': direct code writing is 'near zero.'"
