          "content": "Cursor uses 13 different AI models. Application complexity not captured by foundation model benchmarks. 'Benchmarks can be misleading.'",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/novartis-ceo-vasant-narasimhan-on-transforming-a-250-year-old-company-5kBHPRUC"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "HealthBench (Cognitive Revolution, Feb 2026)",
          "content": "5,000 conversations, 49,000 evaluation criteria, 260 physician cohort. HealthBench Hard: 0% (GPT-4o) to 40% (current models). An attempt to build meaningful evaluation for high-stakes domains rather than synthetic tasks.",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/approaching-the-ai-event-horizon-part-1-w-james-zou-sam-hammond-shoshannah-tekofsky-8teapi/"
        },
        {
          "session": 20,
          "source": "The a16z Show - Misra & Casado (17 March 2026)",
          "content": "Misra implicitly challenges benchmark-driven progress narratives by distinguishing between incremental improvement (measurable on existing benchmarks) and paradigmatic leaps (which by definition aren't captured by benchmarks designed for the current paradigm). Alpha Evolve's matrix multiplication improvements are measurable; 'could it have come up with a new leap like the transformers architecture' is not. The question 'is incremental hill climbing all that's needed from here or do we actually need one or two more big breakthroughs' frames the core limitation of benchmark-driven evaluation.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/whats-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin-casado-YRValfqT"
        },
        {
          "session": 28,
          "source": "The a16z Show - What's Missing Between LLMs and AGI (17 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/whats-missing-between-llms-and-agi-vishal-misra-martin-casado-YRValfqT",
          "content": "Misra distinguishes incremental hill-climbing (what current AI systems do well — Alpha Evolve optimising matrix multiplication) from paradigm leaps (inventing the transformer architecture). Current benchmarks measure hill-climbing performance but don't capture the capacity for leaps. The gap between LLMs and AGI may be one or two fundamental breakthroughs, not just more scaling."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Dwarkesh - Tao (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Tao: 'AI tools are getting really good at the first part — trying all the standard techniques on a problem, often making fewer mistakes than humans. That's the median level of what AI can accomplish.' But: 'on any given problem an AI tool has a success rate of maybe 1% or 2%.' The 80% that AI can solve uses existing methods. The 20% that reaches top journals requires 'a new technique' — a conceptual construction AI can't generate.",
          "url": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/terence-tao"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Dwarkesh - Tao (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Selection bias in AI progress reporting: 'If you only focus on the success stories, it looks amazing. But whenever we do a systematic study, on any given problem an AI tool has a success rate of maybe 1% or 2%.' The gap between curated demos and systematic performance is the AI evaluation crisis. Tao also distinguishes 'artificial cleverness' (trial-and-error jumping) from intelligence (cumulative, interactive progress-building).",
          "url": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/terence-tao"
        },
        {
          "session": 42,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Why AI Needs Better Benchmarks (2026-03-26)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Why-AI-Needs-Better-Benchmarks-e3h1coa",
          "content": "Full benchmark saturation retrospective: MMLU at 88.7% (GPT-4.0, May 2024); GPQA Diamond at 83.3% (O3, summer 2025); SweeBench Pro 57.7% (GPT-5-4); TerminalBench 2.0 65.4% (Anthropic). Each benchmark abandoned when saturated. Benchmark maxing: 'one common perception and critique of Chinese labs is benchmark maxing in the extreme, which frequently leaves their models with a huge gap between their benchmark scores and real-world performance.' SWE Rebench (Feb): Chinese models 'dived in rankings' on different problem set. Meta Llama 4: 'tested multiple model variants on LMArena... when people got their hands on Llama 4, they did not in almost any case think it was the second-best model available.' ARC AGI 3: frontier models <1% vs human 100% on 135 interactive graphical games. François Chollet: 'The benchmark's target, the residual gap between what's hard for AI and what's easy for humans. It's meant to be a tool to measure AGI progress and to drive researchers towards the most important open problems on the way to AGI.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 46,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Anthropic Accidentally Revealed Their Most Powerful Model Ever (2026-03-27)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Anthropic-Accidentally-Revealed-Their-Most-Powerful-Model-Ever-e3h2l87",
          "content": "Cursor Composer 2 controversy: described as 'just Kimmy K2.5 with some extra reinforcement learning applied' by ex-user Flynn, yet beat Opus 4.6 on coding benchmarks. Critics questioned whether this constitutes genuine advancement. LeetLLM: 'seeing an open weight Kimmy 2.5 fine-tune actually beat it on coding benchmarks is wild.' Illustrates how benchmark performance can be achieved via fine-tuning without full pre-training, raising questions about what benchmarks actually measure."
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
        {
          "theme": "T07",
          "reasoning": "investment economics"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T01",
          "reasoning": "enterprise adoption confusion from benchmark noise"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T43",
          "reasoning": "Benchmark limitations (T06) obscure vertical model performance — domain-specific fine-tunes may outperform frontier models on real tasks while appearing inferior on general benchmarks."
        }
      ]
