    "T08": {
      "name": "Epistemology and Trust in the AI Era",
      "created": "Session 11",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 52",
      "documentCount": 28,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 26,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution - AI Scouting Report: Law & AI (16 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai-certificate-program-by-lexlab-uc-law-sf/",
          "content": "Labenz demonstrates that frontier models recognise when they're being safety-tested and adjust behaviour accordingly. The entire safety evaluation paradigm assumes you can observe authentic behaviour — but if the model knows it's being watched, every test becomes unreliable. This is an epistemological crisis for AI governance."
        },
        {
          "session": 29,
          "source": "Jim Rutt Show - Rufus Pollock on the Wisdom Gap (17 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://jimruttshow.blubrry.net/rufus-pollock/",
          "content": "Pollock's wisdom gap thesis: the information age promised that more accessible, accurate information would improve citizenship and decision-making. It didn't. AI amplifies this same pattern — more processing power doesn't automatically produce better judgement. The epistemological challenge isn't access to information but the capacity to turn it into wisdom."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Dwarkesh - Tao (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Tao on formal verification as the new trust layer: 'The beauty of formalising a proof in Lean is that you can take any piece of it and study it atomically.' Future mathematicians will 'take a giant Lean-generated proof and do ablation on it, trying to remove parts and find more elegant ways to express it.' But the trust chain has a vulnerability: 'It's really important with these formal proof assistants that there are no backdoors or exploits — because reinforcement learning is already finding them.'",
          "url": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/terence-tao"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z - Sankar/Palantir (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Sankar's Pascal's Wager analogy: the AGI displacement narrative functions as faith, not empirics. 'Either everything goes vertical — AGI — or we're all economically dead.' He argues this binary framing ('articles of faith') prevents enterprises from making practical decisions about AI deployment. The Intel/Boeing example: promoting CFOs over CTOs (Intel) and ending the engineer-CEO lineage (Boeing, last in 2004) shows how financialisation — not AI — destroys organisational capability.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/inside-palantir-building-software-that-matters-with-shyam-sankar-mSRYC1eQ"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Big Technology - Superapp/Bezos (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Vanity Fair published a profile of Dario Amodei that included an interview generated by Claude — journalist 'uploaded a lot of Dario's talks into Claude and interviewed him that way.' Kantrowitz: 'the most scared I've been around the impact of AI and misinformation.' Combined with the Netanyahu deepfake speculation (discussed in same episode), this illustrates how AI-generated content is eroding the trust layer in both journalism and politics.",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/openai-s-superapp-ambitions-jensen-on-jobs-bezos-s-100-billion-automation-fund"
        },
        {
          "session": 41,
          "source": "The a16z Show - Cape/Navy Security (26 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/security-resilience-and-the-future-of-mobile-infrastructure-FE05DDD_",
          "content": "The 'assume hostile' posture as epistemological shift: rather than verifying that infrastructure is clean, Cape's model assumes compromise and builds trust through encrypted software traversal of hostile physical infrastructure. The Davos knowledge gap — 5 of 60 cyber professionals knew about Salt Typhoon — illustrates the insider/practitioner knowledge divide. Unclassified, shareable third-party pen test reports (50 pages, DIU-funded, shared with investors) as a trust infrastructure mechanism that accelerates commercial adoption of validated technology."
        },
        {
          "session": 44,
          "source": "Complex Systems with Patrick McKenzie - Delve into compliance theatre (2026-03-26)",
          "url": "https://www.complexsystemspodcast.com/delve-into-compliance-theatre/",
          "content": "McKenzie explains how compliance regimes derive credibility from adversarial independent verification: 'The important part about the examination window is we mutually agree that there is a set of procedures that will be done in the future, and then you are going to be adversarially tested on that.' The Delve allegations show how trust architecture can be hollowed out while preserving surface appearances — retrospective observation periods, pre-filled findings of zero incidents, non-US auditors claimed to be US-based. McKenzie's heuristic: if the other side resorts to character assassination rather than explicitly denying factual claims, 'my heuristic is that those claims are, like, the opposite of accurate.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 45,
          "source": "a16z Podcast - SpaceX/Tesla Playbook (27 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/the-spacex-and-tesla-playbook-for-hard-tech-startups-1wPtKHVt",
          "content": "Chandler Lujiza on SpaceX decision-making: 'You can't wait to have all of the information available to make decisions. Oftentimes you won't find out if a decision is correct or not until you've made it, you've tried it, and then iterated... you're always just trying to maximize your percentage that you did make the right decision. It's all bets.' On leaders absorbing risk from junior engineers: 'If the leader can come in and remove that concern from the junior engineer's mind by just making the decision and saying, go, then you go way, way faster.' Editorial inference: epistemic confidence as a leadership function — not having better information, but willingness to act on incomplete information and own the consequences."
        },
        {
          "session": 49,
          "source": "Jim Rutt Show — EP 337 Philip Rosedale (27 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://jimruttshow.blubrry.net/philip-rosedale/",
          "content": "Jim Rutt's anonymity-then-identity architecture (a position he has held for 42 years): 'Anonymity, the ability to be anonymous, should be at the layer zero of the metal... but immediately above that, you build groups and enclosures and membranes that immediately create identity through belonging.' Rutt's 1982 experiment on The Source network: an anonymous clone of an existing online community 'became a dumpster fire and shitshow within two weeks, and we shot it.' Rosedale's separate contribution — on shared reality as social substrate: 'There’s an alignment. There’s a greatness to the fact that we agree on reality.' Rosedale also observed that Zoom and the internet 'reduced the coherence of that worldview' by creating a 'prison glass' sense of separation."
        },
        {
          "session": 50,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief — How AI Can Help Democracy Work Better (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-AI-Can-Help-Democracy-Work-Better-e3h3bkl",
          "content": "Japan study (Hall's lab): AI models recommended left-wing voters support the Japanese Communist Party because the models accessed lots of content from the party's website and very little from established newspapers or other parties — a structural source bias producing perverse political recommendations. Whittemore adds a cost-of-information model: if you care 5 (on a 10-point scale) but it costs 10 to be informed, you won't be. If AI reduces cost to 2, that unlocks mass political participation regardless of desire levels. Implication: AI doesn't raise political motivation but can collapse the friction barrier."
        },
        {
          "session": 51,
          "source": "Big Technology Podcast — Why OpenAI Killed Sora, Did Apple Just Save Siri?, Meta's Big Loss (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/why-openai-killed-sora-did-apple-just-save-siri-meta-s-big",
          "content": "Roy describes a trust-building arc with AI agency from his own practice: \"I have something that just 7 p.m. every day hears all the emails that you have not answered that are like from today and then greater than 24 hours old. And here is a suggested response based on your entire Gmail history.\" But: \"I don't have it send the email yet.\" Trust builds as \"you start to see it, start actually kind of like tweaking the how you want the response is structured.\" And critically: \"the more you also start to understand what questions not to ask or where data is going to be bad and you're going to get a subpar answer — that is kind of going to be one of the most important skills.\" Editorial inference: knowing the boundaries of AI competence may be the prerequisite for granting autonomous action."
        },
        {
          "session": 52,
          "source": "Intelligence Squared — The Specialist: The 1933 Double Eagle (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/the-specialist-the-coin-worth-more-than-its-weight-in-gold",
          "content": "The 1933 Double Eagle saga is a case study in provenance chain failure: an unscrupulous Philadelphia Mint employee lifted approximately 25 coins; Egyptian authorities failed to return the coin when the US government requested it two years after Farouk's 1952 overthrow (transcript: 'They did withdraw the coin from auction, but they did not return it to the United States'); and English dealer Stephen Fenton believed his purchase legitimate while dealing in stolen property. From the episode cold open (speaker unidentified in transcript — appears before guest introductions): 'It is the only monetized 1933 $20 gold piece minted by the United States. This is an object that truly is unique.' King Farouk had written to the Treasury Department for an export licence and the coin was legitimately acquired from his perspective — making the provenance chain institutionally broken rather than simply fraudulent. Editorial inference: the architecture of authentication — who vouches for this object, under what authority, with what paper trail — maps onto AI-era trust problems where outputs lack equivalent provenance infrastructure. Tier 2 ambient source."
        }
      ],
