    "T10": {
      "name": "Job Displacement and the Social Contract",
      "created": "Session 11",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 48",
      "documentCount": 33,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief (19 March)",
          "content": "Anthropic survey — economic mobility is the most speculative of all tension pairs. Both hope and fear are largely hypothetical. But the distribution is telling: independent workers capture benefits at 3x institutional employees' rate. Employees with side projects benefit most (58% reporting real economic gains). Freelancers as 'exposed middle' — 23% living benefits, 17% living downsides. Anthropic: 'AI is both their tool and their competitor.'",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/What-People-Really-Want-From-AI-e3gn965"
        },
        {
          "session": 25,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - A Guy Used AI to Cure His Dog's Cancer (16 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/A-Guy-Used-AI-to-Cure-His-Dogs-Cancer-e3ghqmv",
          "content": "ServiceNow CEO McDermott predicts 30%+ unemployment for recent graduates. Current data: 5.6% unemployment but 42.5% underemployment (highest since 2020). Computer science majors at 7% unemployment. The gap between headline stats and lived experience fuels discourse."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Big Technology - Sorkin (18 Mar)",
          "content": "Sorkin frames 25% unemployment as the realistic endgame if AI succeeds: 'if you ever wanted to think about what would this country look like with 25% unemployment, how would you get there? The answer is AI.' His contract example — ChatGPT replacing a small-business lawyer for basic review — demonstrates the mechanism at individual scale.",
          "url": "https://www.podbean.com/ew/dir-wk4vx-2c0c8512"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Moonshots - GTC Roundup (21 Mar)",
          "content": "CS placement rates collapsed: 'One professor's numbers dropped from near 90% to under 20% across just a few years.' Expert guidance: 'Retrain, become an AI user, or become an entrepreneur. They emphasise ownership and equity as the main path to prosperity.' Diamandis: 'once workflows become agent to agent, human-to-human latency becomes the constraint.'",
          "url": "https://www.youtube.com/@PeterDiamandis/search?query=NVIDIA%27s%20%241%20Trillion%20Prediction%2C%20Anthropic%20Beats%20OpenAI%2C%20Tes"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Layoff Theatre (22 Mar)",
          "content": "Resume.org survey of 1,000 hiring managers: 60% said they emphasised AI's role in layoffs because it's 'viewed more favourably by stakeholders than saying layoffs are due to budget cuts.' Only 9% said AI had actually fully replaced any roles. Block laid off 40% of workforce. 'When a company frames cuts as proactive restructuring, the market penalty disappears' — AI framing provides narrative cover for restructuring that would happen regardless.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Why-AI-Actually-Wont-Take-Your-Job-e3gq5op"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Rules Battle (23 Mar)",
          "content": "HSBC weighing 20,000 layoffs (10% of global headcount) — 'the bank bets on AI to cut headcount in middle and back office functions.' Bloomberg Intelligence predicted 200,000 banking positions eliminated over 3-5 years. Survey of banking CTOs found 'they expect 3% workforce reductions on average.' Zuckerberg building an AI agent to 'help him do his job' focused on 'making information sharing more efficient.'",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/The-Coming-AI-Rules-Battle-e3gs7cm"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z - Sankar/Palantir (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Sankar rejects the replacement thesis: 'I'm not sure why the goal is replacing people to begin with.' His 'iron man suit' metaphor: AI should make operators superhuman, not redundant. On AGI displacement fears: compares them to Pascal's Wager — 'the labs have filled that hole with AGI' as an article of faith, not empirical reality. The Israel reservist case: 360,000 reservists with 20 years of industry experience modernised the IDF more in 4 months than the prior 10 years — proving that civil-military tech transfer works through augmentation, not replacement.",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/inside-palantir-building-software-that-matters-with-shyam-sankar-mSRYC1eQ"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z Podcast - AI Just Gave You Superpowers (19 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-just-gave-you-superpowers-now-what-w1BZEEnu",
          "content": "The 'hollow economy' trajectory: companies 'can do a lot more with less,' starting with 'below average or average performers because AI is already there and younger performers because now the senior one can already scale 100x.' The 'missing junior loop': 'we're not training our future class of verifiers.' Codifier's curse: 'as the expert trains, makes decisions, those labels can be used in the future to do the same decisions without the expert.' LTCM cited as historical analogue for rational-model-driven systemic collapse. Catalini: 'society hasn't really grappled with some of those effects. There's going to be a massive need for retraining.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 38,
          "source": "Big Technology - Warner (25 Mar)",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/senator-mark-warner-nobody-s-ready-for-what-ai-could-do-to",
          "content": "Warner reports 'a nationally known law firm that has decided to hire no first year associates' — a concrete leading indicator from a regulated profession. Graduate unemployment at 9%. Warner: 'short term, next three to five years, the economic disruption is going to be' significant. He frames the workforce data problem: 'We don't have good data' on AI-driven displacement because existing measurement systems weren't built for this speed of change."
        },
        {
          "session": 42,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Why AI Needs Better Benchmarks (2026-03-26)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Why-AI-Needs-Better-Benchmarks-e3h1coa",
          "content": "Senator Mark Warner: 'The recent college graduate unemployment is 9%. I\\'ll bet anyone in the room it goes to 30 or 35% before 2028.' Warner said he 'now believes the scope of the economic disruption is going to be exponentially larger than he thought just a few months ago.' Sanders-AOC data centre moratorium bill requires 'protections for workers and consumers' as prerequisite for lifting construction pause. Warner separately supports codifying Anthropic's red lines on 'domestic surveillance and autonomous weaponry' — the governance and displacement concerns are linked in his framing."
        },
        {
          "session": 43,
          "source": "Moonshots - EP#242 - Elon's $5T Bet (26 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.youtube.com/@PeterDiamandis/search?query=Elon%27s+%245+Trillion+Bet%2C+the+End+of+Human+Drivers%2C+and+Chamat",
          "content": "Concrete workforce displacement signals: Goldman Sachs says AI could automate 25% of US work hours. PWC told partners: 'If you resist AI, you have no place here. AI tool yourself or get out.' G42 posted a job listing exclusively for AI agents — Alex: 'We are so painfully close to a near future where there's a sort of reverse discrimination against humans and where humans need not apply ends up being an epithet.' Dave: companies implementing 80% token cost / 20% salary targets. Sem: 'you'll be able to run a typical company with between 20 or 25% of the employees you have today because all workflow goes from human to human to agent to agent.' Caveat: 'no perturbation in jobs almost zero — we'll just end up creating four or five times more companies.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 48,
          "source": "Intelligence Squared - Why Are Populists Winning? With Liam Byrne and Will Hutton (27 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/why-are-populists-winning-with-liam-byrne-and-will-hutton",
          "content": "Liam Byrne: 'you've got about 1.2 billion people about to join the labour market in poorer countries. Those countries are only going to create about 400 million jobs.' This labour market data is cited as the migration-pressure driver of future populism. Separately, AI is listed as a distinct force that 'could make that problem far worse' — where 'that problem' is the general economic disillusionment ('the great disillusion') driving populist politics, not the labour market shortfall specifically. Byrne's framing: populism is a response to real conditions, not a messaging failure: 'it's not even a grievance. It's a reality.' Tier 2 source — political economy context, not enterprise AI analysis."
        }
