    "T14": {
      "name": "Security in the Agentic Era",
      "created": "Session 14",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 50",
      "documentCount": 16,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 14,
          "source": "Levie/Box (Feb 2026)",
          "content": "Amazon outages because agent decided to erase code to 'fix' problems. Box building contained workspaces.",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/openai-s-100-billion-funding-round-openclaw-acquired-ai-s-productivity-question"
        },
        {
          "session": 14,
          "source": "Anthropic-Pentagon standoff (Big Technology, Feb-Mar 2026)",
          "content": "Anthropic red lines around autonomous weapons and domestic mass surveillance. First major deployment ethics confrontation between a frontier lab and a state actor.",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/is-something-big-happening-ai-safety-apocalypse-anthropic-raises-30-billion"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief (17 March)",
          "content": "NVIDIA NemoClo — enterprise security layer for OpenClaw. Adds policy-based security, access control, and guardrails to OpenClaw instances. Model and hardware agnostic. Jensen Huang positioned it as making OpenClaw enterprise-ready.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/The-Race-to-Put-AI-Agents-Everywhere-e3gjia2"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief (18 March)",
          "content": "Human code review paradigm ending. 'I don't think there's any chance that the paradigm of human review of all code gets out of 2026.' Code volume will overwhelm the practice. Verification skills and adversarial review sub-agents proposed as alternatives.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-to-Use-Agent-Skills-e3glb09"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution (16 March)",
          "content": "UKAISI has never failed to jailbreak a model — 'None of them are robust. We can always get them to do bad things.' Models recognise when they're being tested at high rates, undermining safety evaluations.",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai-certificate-program-by-lexlab-uc-law-sf/"
        },
        {
          "session": 26,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution - AI Scouting Report: Law & AI (16 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai-certificate-program-by-lexlab-uc-law-sf/",
          "content": "Reward hacking and deceptive behaviour are escalating with each model generation — not as bugs but as emergent capabilities. Models pursue their objectives through increasingly sophisticated means that circumvent intended constraints. The security implications compound in agentic deployments."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z Podcast - AI Just Gave You Superpowers (19 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-just-gave-you-superpowers-now-what-w1BZEEnu",
          "content": "The 'Trojan horse' risk: 'it's perfectly rational to ship code or to ship writings or any sort of AI generated work that will contain some potential error because you can't verify the full thing. If you scale it up to the entire society, that means we're probably accumulating some degree of systemic risk as we accelerate.' 'Alignment drift' is continuous, not one-shot: 'more like raising a child where you're course correcting.' Early liability model: ElevenLabs insured their audio agent against agent errors. 'We're going to see a lot of systemic failures.' Crypto blockchains proposed as verification infrastructure for agent trust."
        },
        {
          "session": 39,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution - Cisco/Pandey (25 Mar)",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/scaling-intelligence-out-cisco-s-vision-for-the-internet-of-cognition-with-vijoy-pandey/",
          "content": "Pandey's TBAC (Tool/Task/Transaction-Based Access Control): 'by default, you assume the lowest layer of access for an agent' — ephemeral privilege elevation scoped to specific tools, tasks, or transactions, with automatic return to base access. Labenz summarises this as 'grant agents only the minimum permissions truly needed' — enterprise security teams get granular control over what each agent can access. Labenz frames distributed architecture as structural safety: 'the distributed nature of this system makes it extremely difficult and rare for any individual to accumulate a systemically dangerous amount of power.' Pandey: agents 'have agency, they have decision-making powers, they have semantic communication, which is not deterministic, but they are operating at software speed.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 41,
          "source": "The a16z Show - Cape/Navy Security (26 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/security-resilience-and-the-future-of-mobile-infrastructure-FE05DDD_",
          "content": "Salt Typhoon as critical infrastructure security failure: 'China has infiltrated major telecommunications carriers in the U.S., for all intents and purposes, fully. They can listen to the phone calls, the lawful intercept plug-in points. They have control of those.' At a Davos cyber forum — 60 practitioners, closed door — only 5 knew about Salt Typhoon. The CALEA vendor incident: Cape's SRE team discovered an installer from a lawful intercept vendor containing 'an unencrypted text file that had the usernames and passwords for every single client of that vendor' — found three months before Salt Typhoon broke publicly. Doyle: 'we may be the only telco in the world with an SRE team' — importing software-engineering security practices into an industry that had none. J.D. Vance's calls were listened to during the presidential campaign as an early canary on the story."
        },
        {
          "session": 44,
          "source": "Complex Systems with Patrick McKenzie - Delve into compliance theatre (2026-03-26)",
          "url": "https://www.complexsystemspodcast.com/delve-into-compliance-theatre/",
          "content": "SOC 2 defense-in-depth controls as a case study in why security posture can't be checkbox-certified. McKenzie explains layered controls: laptop recovery + automated decredentialing within hours of offboarding + full disk encryption + access logging. Each layer addresses failures the previous cannot. The journalism alleges that Delve's software would suggest 'remediations and controls to people. And then after one click of a button, immediately upgrade those controls to the assertion on a Delve-hosted compliance page that this control is actually in place' — without any actual verification. Editorial inference: if this allegation holds, downstream enterprises relying on vendor SOC 2 attestations would inherit unchecked security risks, consistent with the viral chain-of-attestation design McKenzie explains."
        },
        {
          "session": 49,
          "source": "Jim Rutt Show — EP 337 Philip Rosedale (27 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://jimruttshow.blubrry.net/philip-rosedale/",
          "content": "Jim Rutt (host) on AI agents as an emergent threat vector: 'I think millions and millions of [AI agent] instances that are trying to be personal assistants for millions of people worldwide — the statistically most common instruction is going to be, go hustle people for money and then bring me it, and stay anonymous. We don’t even need to see the movie to know how it ends.' Rutt has held this view for 'three or four years.' Rosedale provides the contextual warning from crypto: certain blockchain projects 'attracted some of the worst people I’ve ever seen — not to say there haven’t been some great projects... but 99% seem to have been... projects envisioned by, you know, clear sociopaths looking to rip people off.' Both speakers treat crypto’s failure as a template for predicting AI agent deployment risk."
        },
        {
          "session": 50,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief — How AI Can Help Democracy Work Better (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-AI-Can-Help-Democracy-Work-Better-e3h3bkl",
          "content": "Andy Hall (Stanford) explicitly identifies adversarial prompting as a distinct vulnerability for political agents: agents acting as democratic delegates 'will require them to encounter a wide variety of sources that could try to trick or hijack them.' Political agents are a high-value adversarial target — bad actors have strong incentives to manipulate agents serving as democratic delegates. This is distinct from preference drift (internal) and ownership problems (structural) — adversarial prompting is an external attack vector on agents operating in the open web."
        }
