    "T21": {
      "name": "Deskilling and the Preservation of Human Capability",
      "created": "Session 11",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 47",
      "documentCount": 21,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "Andrew Yang: UBI Before UHI, Solving Job Loss (Moonshots #236, Mar 2026)",
          "content": "Yang: entrepreneurship as the only reliable path when general knowledge work is commoditised — but most people aren't cut out for it. Deskilling argument at population scale.",
          "url": "https://open.spotify.com/episode/2xLIHJDUHBzjKl55fERdCv"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "EV Newsletter Lantern and Flame (13 March)",
          "content": "Two new academic citations — Shaw and Nave, 'Thinking-Fast, Slow, and Artificial' (SSRN 2026); Kosmyna et al., 'Your brain on ChatGPT: Accumulation of cognitive debt' (arXiv 2025). First formal academic sources for T21 in the corpus.",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/the-lantern-and-the-flame"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "No Priors Simon Last (12 March)",
          "content": "The adoption gap as a T21 dimension — 'The minimum bar has not changed but the maximum bar has extremely increased.' T21's concern is not just cognitive surrender — it's also the structural disadvantage of non-adoption.",
          "url": "https://www.youtube.com/@NoPriorsPodcast/search?query=From%20Coder%20to%20Manager%3A%20Navigating%20the%20Shift%20to%20Agentic%20Engin"
        },
        {
          "session": 17,
          "source": "Intelligence Squared - Frostlines (14 March 2026)",
          "content": "Norse Greenland colony as historical case study in preservation-over-adaptation failure. Shea: 'The Norse could see these people who were doing well in the Arctic, but they did not become more like them... There was some line they weren't willing to cross, even as the world sort of seemed to close down around them.' The Norse maintained their cultural identity for nearly 500 years in Greenland while the Inuit thrived as neighbours using better-adapted methods. The colony collapsed. Shea frames this as a lesson: 'Are we willing to change or are we going to sort of vanish like the Norse did?' Useful as an analogy for the deliberate preservation problem — but inverted. T21 typically concerns preserving human capability against AI erosion. The Norse case shows the opposite failure mode: preserving identity so rigidly that adaptation becomes impossible. Both are preservation problems; the question is what you preserve and what you let go.",
          "url": "https://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/what-is-really-at-stake-at-the-north-pole-with-neil-shea"
        },
        {
          "session": 22,
          "source": "Intelligence Squared - Frostlines (14 March 2026)",
          "content": "Extended detail on the Norse Greenland case. Shea: 'The Norse could see these people who were doing well in the Arctic, but they did not become more like them... There was some line they weren't willing to cross, even as the world sort of seemed to close down around them.' The Norse maintained farms, European cultural practices, and Norse identity for nearly 500 years in Greenland while Inuit neighbours thrived using better-adapted methods. The colony collapsed. Shea frames this as a question for the present: 'Are we willing to change or are we going to sort of vanish like the Norse did?' Separately, Marvin (age ~27, Gjoa Haven, King William Island) serves as a living case study in cultural preservation under pressure — raised by parents who never learned English and lived nomadically, he translates between an Inuktitut-speaking, land-based past and an English-speaking, wage-earning present. His father Jacob used English only for jokes; serious matters required Inuktitut. As elders of Jacob's generation die, the world Marvin bridges is 'drifting further and further into the distance.' The caribou decline compounds this: Bathurst herd down to fewer than 6,000 animals from hundreds of thousands. Communities that define themselves as 'caribou people' face an identity crisis when the animal that anchors their language, skills, and seasonal rhythms disappears. The preservation problem here is not abstract — it is the loss of the ecological system that made the preserved knowledge functional.",
          "url": "https://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/what-is-really-at-stake-at-the-north-pole-with-neil-shea"
        },
        {
          "session": 26,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution - AI Scouting Report: Law & AI (16 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai-certificate-program-by-lexlab-uc-law-sf/",
          "content": "Legal profession as case study in deskilling: AI performs contract analysis, case research, and brief drafting at expert level. Labenz's 90-slide presentation covers capabilities most lawyers haven't encountered. The question: what's the residual professional skill when AI handles the analytical heavy lifting?"
        },
        {
          "session": 29,
          "source": "Jim Rutt Show - Rufus Pollock on the Wisdom Gap (17 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://jimruttshow.blubrry.net/rufus-pollock/",
          "content": "Pollock's career arc (Open Knowledge Foundation → Life Itself → wisdom cultivation) mirrors the deskilling concern: technology that makes information processing effortless may atrophy the human capacity for deep thinking and judgement that produces wisdom. The 'Second Renaissance' requires preserving — not replacing — human cognitive capabilities."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Dwarkesh - Tao (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Tao: 'I've heard programmers report that even if an AI can create the first prototype, making it mesh with everything else and interact with the real world is an ongoing effort.' On complementarity: 'You'll get a lot more mileage out of the interplay of humans collaborating with these tools.' The 80/20 split implies the human 20% — conceptual synthesis, taste, theory construction — becomes MORE valuable as AI handles the 80%, not less. This inverts the deskilling thesis.",
          "url": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/terence-tao"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Dwarkesh - Tao (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Tao's first-person productivity data: AI gives him '5x on auxiliary tasks' (literature search, code prototyping, data analysis) but hasn't sped up core mathematical work at all. The world's top mathematician confirms: AI amplifies breadth but doesn't touch depth. 'We have to redesign the way we do science to take full advantage of this breadth capability' — the prescription is restructuring work around AI's strengths, not expecting it to replace human depth.",
          "url": "https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/terence-tao"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z Podcast - AI Just Gave You Superpowers (19 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-just-gave-you-superpowers-now-what-w1BZEEnu",
          "content": "The Codifier's Curse: 'as the expert trains, makes decisions, those labels can be used in the future to do the same decisions without the expert.' Top verifiers 'need to keep moving up the stack because the technology gets better and better.' Earlier parallel: 'people were labeling images for AI companies and training. That's not needed anymore.' 'The apprenticeship might be dead, but the real work is beginning.' Lazarin: writing code by hand is 'a hobby now. No one's doing that anymore.' The codifier's curse means 'if you're a top verifier you need to keep moving up the stack right because the technology gets better.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 36,
          "source": "a16z Podcast — Submarines and the Future of Defense Manufacturing (25 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/submarines-and-the-future-of-defense-manufacturing-KGko_EJ6",
          "content": "Chris Power (Hadrian): 'The biggest misconception is it's all automated — we don't need the people. The amount of software engineers, the amount of smart people from Tesla and SpaceX... and the amount of workforce development. It has to be a national mission and it's all about the people and the productivity combined.' Goal: augment machinists, welders and quality inspectors to be '90% more productive', not replace them. Admiral Goucher: workers in some areas are 'less than 50% productive today' — 'by using machines, we have an opportunity to actually get that productivity up so that not only are we able to run around the clock, we're able to be more effective in doing it.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 47,
          "source": "Exponential View Podcast - Solving Problems with the Karpathy Loop (2026-03-27)",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/solving-problems-with-the-karpathy",
          "content": "Azhar articulates the evolving human role: 'your role moves from doing the work to judging the work.' He compares to managing employees: 'I'm used to getting people who are working for me to give me interim updates and for me to course correct them.' The challenge is doing this 'at a much higher cadence than I ever have before' — reading through 'quite long documents' (each round 'maybe a thousand-word markdown document') and determining: 'that's heading in the right direction, or that's not heading in the right direction.'"
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
