        },
        {
          "theme": "T08",
          "reasoning": "epistemology and trust"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T22",
          "reasoning": "taste gap as specific deskilling instance"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T01",
          "reasoning": "The Norse Greenland narrative adds a historical dimension to the enterprise diffusion gap. Organisations that can see AI-native competitors thriving but refuse to adopt fundamentally different working methods — choosing to preserve existing processes and identity — face an analogous adaptation failure. The Norse didn't lack information about what worked; they lacked willingness to change what they considered essential to their identity. This mirrors enterprises where the barrier to AI adoption is not technical capability or even awareness, but organisational identity ('we don't work that way')."
        },
