          "content": "Skills as the convergent design pattern across the entire AI stack. 'AI is less and less a one-off conversation and more and more a library of reliable, repeatable capabilities.' Notion, Codex, Claude Code, Cursor all converging on skills.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-to-Use-Agent-Skills-e3glb09"
        },
        {
          "session": 1,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief (17 March)",
          "content": "Q2 2026 as the productisation sprint — the shift from experimentation to enterprise-ready deployment.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/The-Race-to-Put-AI-Agents-Everywhere-e3gjia2"
        },
        {
          "session": 17,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Coolest Agents (14 March 2026)",
          "content": "Whittemore's 16-agent inventory confirms 'massive shift over the last 3–4 months' in agent building. Key architectural pattern: interconnected agent ecosystem where Holmes (individual profiler) pulls weekly updates from 221B (knowledge hub), and an OpenCLAW coder writes researcher output to a database automatically. Agents have named roles, persistent memory (case files with identity, AI profile, working style, decision-making patterns), and multi-surface presence (web interface + Slack DMs + thread invocation). The ecosystem design — not individual agents — is the unit of value.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/The-Coolest-Agents-Ive-Built-So-Far-e3geoup"
        },
        {
          "session": 33,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - How to Use Agent Skills (2026-03-18)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-to-Use-Agent-Skills-e3gp0v5",
          "content": "Multi-agent orchestration as work primitive: skills are composed into loops where agents hand off to each other based on defined decision boundaries. The loop structure — sense, decide, act, evaluate — is the fundamental unit of agentic work."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "EV Podcast - Azhar/GTC (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Azhar's OpenClaw usage reveals agent economics at the individual level: 'close enough to a billion tokens per day — it was 100 million two or three weeks ago.' The 10x jump in personal token consumption in weeks illustrates how agentic loops compound: each agent spawns sub-tasks, each sub-task generates tokens, and the demand curve steepens as agents become more capable.",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/jensen-openclaw-and-the-future-of"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "EV Newsletter - Harness Thesis (21 Mar)",
          "content": "Azhar's personal token growth: 150,000/day (summer 2024) → 100m/day (two weeks ago) → 870m in one day (this week). Three orders of magnitude in under two years. His OpenClaw setup: Mini Arnold (chief of staff) delegates to four sub-agents — Veblen (book research), Simmons (portfolio), Bradlee (editorial), Gulbenkian (AI economy frameworks). The 'leave it to its own devices' threshold was crossed at the end of 2025 with Claude Code.",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/jensens-openclaw-thesis"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "a16z Podcast - AI Just Gave You Superpowers (19 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://a16z.simplecast.com/episodes/ai-just-gave-you-superpowers-now-what-w1BZEEnu",
          "content": "The 'AI sandwich' org structure named explicitly: 'one single human...called a director...in charge of steering, verification, making sure that as the system drifts in directions not intended, we can course correct. In the middle, a swarm of agents. At the bottom, an army or small army of top verifiers.' Lazarin: 'humans are not going to do verification line by line. The throughput of the machines is accelerating too fast for that. But with the right tools, I think the top experts in every domain are going to be the ones ensuring that what was intended actually came out of the system.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 47,
          "source": "Exponential View Podcast - Solving Problems with the Karpathy Loop (2026-03-27)",
          "url": "https://www.exponentialview.co/p/solving-problems-with-the-karpathy",
          "content": "AutoResearch described as archetypal agentic loop: 'You change one thing. The agent picks a hypothesis. It sees how well that hypothesis performs. It measures that. And if it's better, it keeps that as a new baseline. And it moves on to another hypothesis.' 'Every experiment takes about five minutes. So you have up to 12 experiments an hour.' AutoWolf extends with escape harness — random perturbation to escape local minima, compared to 'evolution's sudden mutations.' Applied to headlines, thesis refinement, commercial reasoning."
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
