    "T27": {
      "name": "The Perception-Capability Divergence",
      "created": "Session 25",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 42",
      "documentCount": 8,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 25,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - A Guy Used AI to Cure His Dog's Cancer (16 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/A-Guy-Used-AI-to-Cure-His-Dogs-Cancer-e3ghqmv",
          "content": "Whittemore's 'AI's second moment' thesis: mainstream sentiment increasingly negative (polls, political rhetoric, media fear) while actual capability accelerates (agent teams, vibe coding, autonomous workflows). SEC filing pattern shows this split within organisations — CEOs dismiss while legal teams disclose. 57% negative polling coincides with 900M ChatGPT users. The people experiencing benefits and the people forming opinions are increasingly different populations."
        },
        {
          "session": 26,
          "source": "Cognitive Revolution - AI Scouting Report: Law & AI (16 Mar 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.cognitiverevolution.ai/ai-scouting-report-the-good-bad-weird-the-law-ai-certificate-program-by-lexlab-uc-law-sf/",
          "content": "Labenz's entire scouting report exists because of the perception-capability divergence: professionals — including lawyers at a leading law school — haven't updated their mental model of what AI can do. He covers 90 slides in 45 minutes because the 'dizzying pace is itself part of the point'."
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "Big Technology - Sorkin (18 Mar)",
          "content": "Software engineer hiring is rising on Indeed even as AI coding capability accelerates — the perception of displacement runs ahead of the reality. Sorkin acknowledges 'we're definitely not seeing a wave of layoffs of software engineers now' but insists the trajectory is clear. Kantrowitz notes the Citrini letter triggered panic (software stocks lost $1 trillion in market cap) despite no actual workforce reduction.",
          "url": "https://www.podbean.com/ew/dir-wk4vx-2c0c8512"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Convergence (20 Mar)",
          "content": "Jensen Huang at GTC: 'The desire to warn people about the capability of the technology is really terrific. But you don't want to do it in a way that demonises the technology.' Huang frames AI pessimism as a national security risk — the gap between public fear and actual capability creates policy paralysis. Americans rank as 'some of if not the least optimistic about the technology.'",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Every-AI-Product-Is-Becoming-Every-Other-AI-Product-e3goh0v"
        },
        {
          "session": 34,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Layoff Theatre (22 Mar)",
          "content": "The AI layoff theatre IS the perception-capability divergence in action — companies claim AI is replacing workers (perception) while the data shows only 9% actual replacement (capability reality). Whittemore: companies are 'using AI as narrative cover' for restructuring that would happen anyway. This amplifies public fear of AI while overstating its actual deployment in workforce automation.",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Why-AI-Actually-Wont-Take-Your-Job-e3gq5op"
        },
        {
          "session": 35,
          "source": "Moonshots - Schmidt/Diamandis (24 Mar)",
          "content": "Schmidt explicitly separates the hype from reality: 'we don't have recursive self-improvement yet.' He names the 'San Francisco consensus' — 'everyone in San Francisco believes this' — that human-equivalent agents are imminent, while positioning himself as acknowledging both the acceleration and the gap. 'We're 10 to 15% into the impacts of this and you can see it, you can feel it.' This 10-15% framing directly challenges both the 'AI will replace everyone' panic and the 'nothing has changed' dismissal.",
          "url": "https://www.youtube.com/@PeterDiamandis/search?query=Eric+Schmidt%3A+Singularity%27s+Arrival%2C+the+92-Gigawatt+Problem"
        },
        {
          "session": 38,
          "source": "Big Technology - Warner (25 Mar)",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/senator-mark-warner-nobody-s-ready-for-what-ai-could-do-to",
          "content": "Warner describes a private-public perception split among AI lab leadership: CEOs 'have changed their pitch and are now holding back because they're freaked out about freaking out people.' Kantrowitz confirms: 'that was marketing language a couple of months ago, but now there's at least a percentage chance that that's real.' Public polling reinforces the gap: 'far more Americans say data centers are mostly bad than good for the environment at 39% to 4%.'"
        },
        {
          "session": 42,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief - Why AI Needs Better Benchmarks (2026-03-26)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/Why-AI-Needs-Better-Benchmarks-e3h1coa",
          "content": "Benchmark maxing as structural perception-capability divergence: 'one common perception and critique of Chinese labs is benchmark maxing in the extreme, which frequently leaves their models with a huge gap between their benchmark scores and real-world performance.' SWE Rebench variant confirmed the gap — Chinese models 'dived in rankings' when tested on a different problem set from SweeBench verified; western models dropped but 'not by nearly as much.' Meta Llama 4: tested variants on LMArena until finding best score, launched as second-ranked model — 'when people got their hands on Llama 4, they did not in almost any case think it was the second-best model available.' The structural incentive to benchmark-max systematically inflates reported capability."
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
        {
          "theme": "T01",
          "reasoning": "The perception-capability divergence (T27) is the macro-level phenomenon that creates the enterprise diffusion gap (T01) — organisations can't adopt what their stakeholders fear"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T10",
          "reasoning": "Job displacement fears (T10) are amplified by the perception-capability divergence (T27) — headline predictions like McDermott's 30% figure feed the fear side while actual productivity data feeds the capability side"
        }
      ]
    },
