          "content": "McKenzie explains the design intent behind compliance officer roles and board resolutions: compliance regimes intentionally route liability to named humans to prevent what he calls (citing Dan Levy's term) 'accountability sinks' — corporations that absorb and diffuse responsibility so no individual is held accountable. McKenzie: 'I, Patrick McKenzie, swear to everybody relevant, including the hospitals we are working with and including ultimately the federal government, that the buck stops with me here.' Board resolutions are a specific design feature — boards must formally adopt policies, creating documented personal liability. The Delve allegations include fabricated board minutes for meetings that never happened. McKenzie: 'If you're signing your board members up for minutes and meetings that did not happen, you're potentially signing them up for legal liability.'"
