          "session": 53,
          "source": "Intelligence Squared — The Crown's Silence (Brooke Newman) (29 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/how-deeply-was-the-british-crown-involved-in-the",
          "content": "Newman describes the Crown's accountability narrative in her own words: \"this idea that it is regrettable that we were involved, but we led the way in abolishing the transatlantic slave trade and ultimately in ending slavery. And so we should be congratulated because we were the champions of abolition. And that narrative is just repeated over and over and over again\" — repeated by royal family members, political leaders, and in schools. She characterises this pattern as claiming the last 5% (abolition) while closing the door on the preceding 95%. Newman also documents how post-2020 institutional slavery studies (University of Glasgow, Bristol, Cambridge, Lloyds of London, Church Commissioners of the Church of England) were initiated, then a chilling effect set in after anti-woke backlash targeted the National Trust — causing many institutions to shut down further work. Editorial inference: accountability architectures that substitute symbolic acknowledgment (\"regrettable\") plus credit-claiming (\"we led abolition\") for structural reckoning follow an evasion pattern directly relevant to how AI governance accountability frameworks can be structured to perform responsibility without assigning it."
        }
      ],
