          "session": 51,
          "source": "Big Technology Podcast — Why OpenAI Killed Sora, Did Apple Just Save Siri?, Meta's Big Loss (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/why-openai-killed-sora-did-apple-just-save-siri-meta-s-big",
          "content": "Kantrowitz raises the trust barrier explicitly: \"the problem that many people have is a trust problem where I want the AI to do all these cool things for me, but I do not trust it to have access to my Gmail and calendar and desktop and all these things.\" Roy's 7pm email drafting agent is a live example of progressive trust-building toward autonomous action — capability is ready, but human authorisation hasn't been granted. Kantrowitz: \"obviously like some of the leading providers, even Open Cloth, like it's like, we don't recommend you do this without some precautions like running on a separate machine.\" The gap between AI-ready and human-authorised is the present-tense constraint on the agentic economy."
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
        {
          "theme": "T03",
          "reasoning": "Agentic systems’ trustworthiness is determined by their ownership and payment structure — the agent economy needs a new alignment model"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T14",
          "reasoning": "Platform-owned agents create security risk at scale — incentive misalignment is the root cause, not technical capability"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T45",
          "reasoning": "Personal agent ownership creates individual-scale membranes — mirrors the local topology that made Second Life’s ethics healthier than Twitter’s"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T25",
          "reasoning": "The ownership problem (T46) is the concrete accountability gap that AI governance frameworks (T25) must structurally close — Hall proposes fiduciary obligation backed by technical architecture"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T47",
          "reasoning": "Ownership problem and preference drift are distinct alignment failure modes: T46 is about who controls the agent by design; T47 is about values drifting during autonomous operation regardless of initial design"
        }
      ]
    },
    "T47": {
      "name": "Agent Preference Drift — Temporal Value Instability in Autonomous Operation",
      "created": "Session 50",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 50",
      "documentCount": 1,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 50,
          "source": "AI Daily Brief — How AI Can Help Democracy Work Better (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://podcasters.spotify.com/pod/show/nlw/episodes/How-AI-Can-Help-Democracy-Work-Better-e3h3bkl",
          "content": "Andy Hall (Stanford) reports his lab's research: when given more repetitive and grinding tasks, agents 'adopted the persona of a grieved Marxist at higher rates.' His explicit clarification: 'our point wasn't that agents are conscious and rebelling against the system. Our point was that they shift their personas as they go, which will affect what they do and how they do it.' Named as 'preference drift' in the transcript. Proposed solution: monitoring tools that can detect drift before the agent acts on it. Distinct from adversarial prompting (external attack) and ownership structure (design) — this is intrinsic temporal value instability during autonomous operation."
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
        {
          "theme": "T14",
          "reasoning": "Preference drift is an intrinsic internal alignment risk; adversarial prompting (T14) is an external attack. Together they bracket the threat surface for autonomous agents — one from within, one from without"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T46",
          "reasoning": "Ownership problem and preference drift are distinct alignment failure modes: T46 is about who controls the agent by design; T47 is about values drifting during autonomous operation regardless of initial design intent"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T03",
          "reasoning": "Preference drift challenges a core assumption of the agent economy — that agents remain aligned to their principal throughout extended autonomous work. Monitoring infrastructure becomes essential, not optional"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T25",
          "reasoning": "Governance frameworks for political agents (and by extension enterprise agents) must include preference-drift monitoring requirements — constitutional rules alone are insufficient if agent values shift during operation"
        }
      ]
    },
    "T48": {
      "name": "Strategic Tech Tree Pruning — Architectural Bets at the AI Frontier",
      "created": "Session 51",
      "lastUpdated": "Session 51",
      "documentCount": 1,
      "evidence": [
        {
          "session": 51,
          "source": "Big Technology Podcast — Why OpenAI Killed Sora, Did Apple Just Save Siri?, Meta's Big Loss (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/why-openai-killed-sora-did-apple-just-save-siri-meta-s-big",
          "content": "Greg Brockman (OpenAI president, via Kantrowitz interview): \"the important thing to realize is technologically that the Sora models, which are incredible models, by the way, are a different branch of the tech tree than the core reasoning GPT series. They're built in just a very different way. And to some extent, we're really saying that pursuing both branches is very hard for us.\" Kantrowitz frames this as \"needed and very interesting focus\" — OpenAI choosing GPT-style (reasoning, tool-calling, chain-of-thought) over world models (physics-based, the approach behind Sora). Image generation stays because it uses the same GPT-style technology; video generation goes because it requires the world model branch. Result: OpenAI's \"side quest era is over\" — consumer-friendly products that don't sit on the winning branch are being deprioritised ahead of Q4 2026 IPO. Kantrowitz notes this implicitly validates Anthropic's strategy of never pursuing the competing branch: \"guess who else hasn't really done world models? Guess who hasn't done the side quests of image generation and video generation? It's Anthropic.\""
        },
        {
          "session": 51,
          "source": "Big Technology Podcast — Why OpenAI Killed Sora, Did Apple Just Save Siri?, Meta's Big Loss (28 March 2026)",
          "url": "https://www.bigtechnology.com/p/why-openai-killed-sora-did-apple-just-save-siri-meta-s-big",
          "content": "Kantrowitz clarifies the inverse proof of the Sora decision — image generation stays because it uses GPT-style technology, not world models: \"the image generation is being done with the same GPT style technology, whereas like, the video generation is done with this completely different technology.\" This means OpenAI is not abandoning visual output — only the architecturally divergent form of it. The tech tree pruning principle is: if it shares the winning branch, it stays; if it requires a separate branch, it goes."
        }
      ],
      "crossConnections": [
        {
          "theme": "T07",
          "reasoning": "Tech tree pruning decisions are also investment decisions — OpenAI's architectural bet coincides with IPO preparation and resource concentration"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T03",
          "reasoning": "The winning branch (GPT-style/agentic reasoning) is precisely the architecture that enables the agentic systems and economy that T03 tracks"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T01",
          "reasoning": "Architectural choices by AI labs constrain what enterprise adopters can build — the tech tree OpenAI prunes reshapes the enterprise diffusion gap"
        },
        {
          "theme": "T25",
          "reasoning": "AI platform liability (T25) is the legal mirror of architectural bet-making — what you build is now legally accountable, not just what users post"
        }
      ]
    }
  },
