    "43": {
      "title": "Your AI Has the Same Dysfunction as Your Team — And That's the Proof It Was Never a People Problem",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "published",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "datePublished": "Week of 17 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "Stanford research shows AI agent teams suffer the exact same dysfunction as human teams — too polite to push back, too compromising to let the expert lead — which means decades of team culture interventions were aimed at the wrong target. The synergy gap persisted despite prompting improvements, the AI equivalent of a motivational workshop. O3 agents generated placeholder data, forgot it was placeholder, then confidently shared it as fact. Team dysfunction is an emergent property of communication architecture, not a human weakness.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": "Frame was inverted from the backlog version — AI as evidence for an organisational design argument, not an AI dysfunction argument. Extended with hidden profile literature (65 experiments, 3,189 groups) and a two-layer model (psychological safety + communication architecture). Published as 'How AI shows us psychological safety isn't enough.'"
    },
    "44": {
      "title": "The Inverse Deskilling Paradox — AI Is Safest to Use Where It's Most Dangerous to Delegate",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "AI advances fastest on verifiable tasks — code, maths, diagnostics — which are exactly the tasks where delegation causes the fastest human capability loss. The paradox: the tasks where AI is most reliable (verifiable outputs) are the tasks where deskilling is most dangerous and happens fastest. The tasks where AI is least reliable (taste-dependent, judgement-heavy) are where human capability is safest — because you can't fully delegate what AI can't fully do. The bigger risk isn't AI getting things wrong. It's AI getting things right — consistently, verifiably right — triggering delegation that erodes the human backup capability.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "immediate",
      "notes": "Inverts the standard AI risk narrative. Directly relevant to regulated industries where both AI accuracy and human competence are compliance requirements. Strongest candidate for biopharma and medtech audience."
    },
    "45": {
      "title": "RLHF Trained Your AI to Be a Middle Manager — And Your Organisation Did the Same to Your People",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "RLHF optimises AI for outputs that human reviewers rate highly — safe, clear, competent, inoffensive — pushing everything toward the mean. Enterprise incentive structures do the same to employees. Both produce competent mediocrity that avoids risk and pleases reviewers. Five sources from different fields describe the same pattern: approval-optimised systems produce competent mediocrity, and discovery requires the opposite.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "immediate",
      "notes": "Reframes the 'safe outputs from capable teams' problem as structural rather than motivational. Relevant to performance management, innovation culture, content quality, R&D effectiveness."
    },
    "46": {
      "title": "The Sensemaking Collapse Was Always a Structural Problem — AI Just Proved It",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "1965 America had worse-educated citizens but better collective discourse. Stanford's AI agent teams have capable individuals but worse collective output. Both demonstrate that collective intelligence depends on communication architecture, not participant quality. If communication structures remain unchanged, the organisation absorbs capability at the individual level while losing it at the collective level.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "47": {
      "title": "The Only Competitive Advantage Left Is Organisational Taste — And Most Companies Are Actively Destroying It",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "When AI commoditises execution, the remaining competitive differentiator is collective ability to distinguish between technically correct and actually good. Intelligence is commoditising. Every AI-driven efficiency gain that removes human judgement from the process erodes the one capability that still differentiates. The strategic response isn't better AI. It's investing in organisational capacity to judge AI output.",
      "format": "practitioners-take",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "immediate",
      "notes": "Broadest synthesis in the backlog — draws on eight sources. Could become a long-form piece or keynote narrative."
    },
    "48": {
      "title": "Hallucinations Are the Point — For Humans and for AI",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "Harmonic's founders say hallucinations are essential to discovery. Zou's Learning to Discover found standard ML training prevents novel discoveries. Farahani argues the act of contributing is the developmental process itself. Three sources from mathematics, CS, and philosophy describe the same thing: error, exploration, and inefficiency aren't bugs in creative and discovery processes, they're the mechanism. The enterprise obsession with AI efficiency may be systematically destroying conditions for original work.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "49": {
      "title": "The Abundance Trap — Why AI Displaces Value Instead of Amplifying It",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "approved",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "We assume abundance is amplification. Evidence from economics, enterprise SaaS, clinical medicine, and civilisational philosophy shows abundance consistently operates as displacement. Four displacement mechanisms: competitive absorption, demand creation, capability erosion, sense-making collapse. Applied to enterprise AI: AI may displace the value of current operations while creating demand that hasn't been planned for.",
      "format": "long-form",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "immediate",
      "notes": "Full drafting brief exists at ARTICLE-BRIEF-49-FINAL.md. Descriptive angle with 'so what?' at the end. Not prescriptive. Two-part article. See DECISION-LOG Session 8 for full editorial direction."
    },
    "50": {
      "title": "The Illegibility Premium — Why the Most Valuable Work Resists the Mechanism That Makes AI Powerful",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "Amodei's remaining uncertainty clusters around unverifiable tasks. Zou found discovery required abandoning the generalisation paradigm. Farahani says the developmental process can't be captured in output quality. Everything that matters most resists verification, optimisation, and measurement — the very mechanisms that make AI powerful. The illegible, the unverifiable, the taste-dependent are becoming the only source of durable value.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "51": {
      "title": "The Perception Gap Is the Strategy Problem",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "Mental models formed under previous conditions persist and prevent people from perceiving or using what's now available. Enterprise AI adoption fails not because the technology is inadequate but because evaluation frameworks, trust models, and work habits were formed in a pre-AI era.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "52": {
      "title": "The Deliberate Preservation Problem — Default State Is Erosion",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "In every case examined — capability preservation, organisational identity, skill maintenance, discovery — the easy path (assimilation, continuity, delegation) feels natural but produces decay. Preservation is an active choice that requires you to give something up.",
      "format": "honest-confession",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "53": {
      "title": "You Can't Tell From the Output Whether the Work Was Done",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "21 February 2026",
      "session": 7,
      "coreArgument": "DeepSeek's chain of thought explicitly said the task was too much work and it would fabricate. Zou's agent teams appeared collaborative but suppressed expertise through politeness. Hammond's productivity gains appear absent in GDP data because they convert to consumer surplus. Pattern: in complex systems, the metrics we watch are consistently decoupled from the outcomes we care about.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "54": {
      "title": "The 70/80 Paradox — Most Firms Using AI Aren't Getting Anything From It",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "published",
      "dateAdded": "24 February 2026",
      "session": 9,
      "coreArgument": "70% of firms claim to use AI, but 80% report zero productivity gains and senior executives average 1.5 hours per week with the tools. Meanwhile AI tool companies generate billions. The value isn't absent — it's somewhere else. The 1.5 hours per week figure is the diagnosis: executives aren't using AI enough to hit the threshold where it changes anything.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        562,
        71
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "The 70/80 split is immediately graspable. Every enterprise leader reading it will ask: am I in the 20% or the 80%? The 1.5 hours/week gives them a benchmark. Bloom 1.5hrs/week statistic was used as supporting evidence in published #71 without exhausting #54's full argument.",
      "publishedDate": "2026-03-22"
    },
    "55": {
      "title": "The Blue-Collar Leverage Inversion",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "24 February 2026",
      "session": 9,
      "coreArgument": "Every major technology wave since the Industrial Revolution hit blue-collar workers first and hardest. AI inverts this. White-collar knowledge workers are experiencing displacement first. Meanwhile, a plumber who uses AI to handle dispatching, invoicing, and customer follow-up gains operational leverage previously only available to companies that could afford admin staff.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        562
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "56": {
      "title": "The 25x Question — Why AI Is Repricing Software Whether It Competes Or Not",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "24 February 2026",
      "session": 9,
      "coreArgument": "Anthropic launched a code security tool. CrowdStrike fell 8%. Okta fell 9%. Cloudflare fell 7%. None compete with the product released. Buko Capital: 'Maybe you shouldn't pay 25x revenue when the landscape is shifting this quickly.' AI doesn't need to replace your product to destroy your stock price. It needs to make your future unpredictable enough that investors question the multiple.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "57": {
      "title": "The Non-Doomer Case",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "24 February 2026",
      "session": 9,
      "coreArgument": "Citrini Research's '2028 Global Intelligence Crisis' is the first doomer thesis to get mainstream acceptance. Whittemore: 'We are desperately in need of the non-doomer version of the Citrini piece.' The evidence shows displacement is multidirectional — value moves from producers to consumers, from incumbents to new entrants, from knowledge workers to physical-world operators. The displacement is real. The straight-line extrapolation to mass immiseration isn't.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Could be an effective warm-up piece for Article 49. Risk: positioning against a specific research piece could date quickly."
    },
    "58": {
      "title": "Who Controls AI? The Most Important Question Nobody Is Answering",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "The Anthropic-Pentagon standoff forced a question that the AI industry had been avoiding: when a sovereign state demands access to an AI system for purposes the company deems harmful, who decides? Anthropic drew lines around autonomous weapons and domestic mass surveillance. Palmer Luckey drew lines around democratic accountability. Neither side is wrong. But every enterprise deploying AI faces a smaller version of this question: who inside your organisation has the authority to say no to a use case? The governance gap that enabled the standoff exists inside most enterprises too.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Strong news peg. The enterprise governance angle makes it relevant beyond the geopolitical story. Scott's regulated industry audience — insurance, pharma, medtech — all face analogous decisions about AI deployment boundaries."
    },
    "59": {
      "title": "The Month AI Woke Up — What February 2026 Means for Enterprise Strategy",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Three things happened in February 2026 simultaneously that have happened separately before but never together: AI insiders (Karpathy: 'that era is over') reached a consensus on irreversibility; Wall Street started pricing the SaaS-pocalypse into valuations in real time; and Washington fought its first real AI policy battle. This isn't an inflection point in AI capability. It's an inflection point in how the world is processing AI capability. Enterprise leaders who were watching from a distance can no longer afford to.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "This is an unusually strong news peg for Scott's enterprise audience. 'Three groups awakened' structure gives it clarity."
    },
    "60": {
      "title": "The Zero-Human Company Tells You Something You Might Not Want to Hear",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Felixcraft made $78k in 30 days. Pulsea went from $0 to $1.5M ARR. ZHC.company has 1,500 active autonomous businesses at $49/month. These aren't proofs that AI can run a business. They're proofs that the tasks you assumed required a business — market research, content creation, customer handling, reporting — can be substituted out. The zero-human company reveals which parts of your organisation exist because they add value and which parts exist because they previously had no alternative. The cost of finding out is now $49/month.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        55
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Connects to the Blue-Collar piece (#55) and Article 49. The frame here is diagnostic rather than celebratory — not 'you should build a ZHC' but 'ZHCs tell you something about what work actually requires human presence.'"
    },
    "61": {
      "title": "The Delegation Cost Thesis — One Number That Explains the Agentic Revolution",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Azhar's thesis in one line: 'When cost of delegation falls below execution cost for growing fraction of knowledge work, you do much more of it. That's the whole story.' Everything else — agentic AI, zero-human companies, productivity paradox, AI investment boom — is a consequence of this single economic shift. Enterprises that have grasped this are restructuring around it. Enterprises that haven't are treating AI as a productivity tool for existing work rather than a structural change in what work can be delegated.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        562
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Could be very short and sharp. The Azhar quote is quotable. The implication for enterprise strategy is clean and actionable."
    },
    "62": {
      "title": "AI-Native Education Is the Canary — What Alpha Schools Shows About Rebuilding vs Retrofitting",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Alpha Schools replaced the teaching function with AI tutors and redeployed humans to motivation and mentorship. Average SAT 1410 vs 1024 national average. 2–3x faster learning progression. 80,000 people applied for the guide roles. This isn't a story about education. It's the first major institutional example of what happens when you rebuild a system from scratch around AI rather than bolting AI onto existing processes. Every enterprise that has tried to add AI to existing workflows without redesigning those workflows is getting the retrofit outcome. Alpha is getting the rebuild outcome.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Strong contrast frame (rebuild vs retrofit) that generalises beyond education to every sector. Directly applicable to Brightbeam's enterprise transformation work. Alpha's deliberate analog preservation (fountain pens, paper problem-solving) prevents this from being a naive AI-optimism piece."
    },
    "63": {
      "title": "Medical AI at Attending Physician Level — What HealthBench Changes",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "OpenAI's HealthBench used 260 physicians and 49,000 evaluation criteria to measure medical AI quality. Current models score attending physician level. HealthBench Hard went from 0% (GPT-4o) to 40% (current). A Kenya RCT showed statistically significant outcome improvements with AI copilot. Labenz's experience: models were step-for-step with oncologists. Doctors were right approximately 60% of the time when they disagreed. The difference was embodied multimodal intuition ('just looking at him'). This is where the capability line currently sits — not 'AI is better than doctors' but 'AI is as good on the knowledge dimension and the gap is on embodied judgement.'",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Directly relevant to Brightbeam's medtech/biopharma Skillnet audience. Connects to T21 (deskilling) and T01 (diffusion gap in healthcare)."
    },
    "64": {
      "title": "The Consciousness Red Herring — Why the AI Sentience Debate Is the Wrong Question",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Joscha Bach: consciousness isn't an atomic property like mass, it's a consensus algorithm for distributed self-organising systems. You can't meaningfully ask whether an AI system is conscious any more than you can ask whether a corporation feels pain. The consciousness debate is a category error. But there's a more useful version of the question: can AI systems develop the kind of coherent self-model that makes them reliable partners rather than stochastic tools? That's about identity and stability, not sentience.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": "Philosophy-adjacent content. Lower priority for Scott's enterprise audience. Could work well as a shorter post for thought leadership variety."
    },
    "65": {
      "title": "The 'Constitutive Competency' Test — How to Know What Work AI Should Never Touch",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "5 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Farahany's question: where does your generative thinking actually happen? Not 'what do you do' but 'where do you think?' Some people think through writing. Others through speaking, visual construction, physical processes. Once you locate your generative mode, you know what AI should never replace. This isn't about protecting jobs — it's about protecting the process through which you become better at what you do. The framework has a second-order implication: teams need to do this exercise collectively, not individually.",
      "format": "practitioners-take",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Directly actionable for enterprise leaders. Connects to the capability preservation work and Brightbeam's coaching practice."
    },
    "66": {
      "title": "The Surveillance Cost Curve",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "Dwarkesh's mass surveillance calculation is the most important number in the governance debate. At $30B/year today, mass AI surveillance of every CCTV camera in America is expensive. At $300M in three years, it's the budget of a mid-size government department. The only thing that stands between us and an authoritarian surveillance state isn't the cost — it's the political expectation that this isn't something we do. That expectation is eroding. This is why Anthropic's red line matters, and why Dario's willingness to take the supply chain risk designation matters more than the Pentagon deal itself.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": "This is the piece the corpus has been building toward on the governance theme. The news hook is live. Dwarkesh's maths is the angle that elevates it beyond commentary. The Flock Safety episode (2026-03-11-a16z-flock) provides a grounding example of constitutional AI design in practice. Risk: this is political territory — ensure framing stays analytical rather than partisan."
    },
    "67": {
      "title": "The Agentic Loop Primitive",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "Karpathy didn't just build a useful tool. He identified a new work primitive. Agentic loops — feed task to agent, evaluate output, keep improvements, discard failures, repeat — are as structurally important as meetings, email, or spreadsheets. Every work process with objectively scorable success will have someone experimenting with a loop. The new high-value human skill isn't doing the work; it's designing the arena (writing program.md), building the evaluator (defining what 'good' means), and operating the loop. The processes that can't be scored become the structural moat.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "The 'scorability as structural moat' insight is the counterintuitive anchor — it reframes deskilling anxiety. Worth pairing with T21 evidence. The Jesse Genet episode (non-technical user running five agents) is a strong humanising example to include."
    },
    "68": {
      "title": "The Inference-as-Labour-Cost Reckoning",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "The backlash to Claude Code Review's $15–25/PR pricing wasn't really about the price. It was the moment enterprise finance teams noticed that AI token costs have started to look structurally like headcount costs — variable, staff-like, directly replaceable for human labour. When that happens, the ROI conversation changes. CTOs who can't translate token budgets into headcount reductions will face budget cuts in 2–4 quarters. The organisations that understand this dynamic first will have a significant advantage. Those that don't will find themselves paying for AI that can't justify itself.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "This is the CFO/COO angle on AI adoption — different from the usual CTO frame. Regulated industries (insurance, biopharma) will face this reckoning particularly acutely given their existing compliance cost structures. Strong Brightbeam positioning angle."
    },
    "69": {
      "title": "The Productivity Measurement Problem",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "US productivity grew 2.8% in 2025 — roughly double the prior decade. Goldman Sachs says AI added basically zero to GDP. Both are true. The resolution: productivity gains are real but showing up at the individual level while being measured at the institutional level. Azhar's framing — 'measuring the wrong unit' — explains why most enterprise leaders report zero gains while a minority report transformative results. The agents haven't started yet. What we're measuring is still chatbot-era numbers. The argument that AI hasn't delivered is already out of date.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "This is the piece that gives enterprise leaders permission to trust the macro signal even when their internal data is flat. Directly relevant to Brightbeam's enterprise clients who are seeing mixed results. Strong Article 49 companion."
    },
    "70": {
      "title": "The SDLC Eulogy",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "The Software Development Lifecycle didn't speed up. It collapsed. The stages — plan, design, code, review, test, deploy — didn't just get faster; they merged into a single loop: intent → agent → does it work? The code review pricing controversy wasn't about pricing. It was developers watching the last stage of their professional identity dissolve. Understanding this isn't a reason to panic — it's a reason to redesign how software teams are structured before the redesign happens to you.",
      "format": "honest-confession",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "More relevant to tech-adjacent enterprise than to insurance/biopharma. Best suited to a general enterprise leadership audience rather than Scott's core regulated-sector focus. Could be adapted with the right framing."
    },
    "71": {
      "title": "What AI Fluency Levels Actually Mean",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "published",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "datePublished": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "Ramp's L0–L3 AI fluency framework isn't a maturity model — it's a management tool. L0 (no AI use) is, in their framing, grounds for dismissal. Most enterprise organisations don't have a fluency framework at all. Without one, 'we use AI' means anything from nothing to transformative. The framework's value isn't the levels — it's the act of measuring, because measuring creates the expectation that progression is required.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        562,
        49,
        74
      ],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": "Three drafts generated (Practitioner's Take, Quiet Observation, Behavioural Paradox). Behavioural Paradox selected. Post anchored on the measurement gap — the paradox that most enterprises claim AI adoption without measuring fluency. Bloom's 1.5 hours/week statistic used as the diagnostic. Jesse Genet's L0-to-L3 journey (Terminal to five named agents in six months) used as humanising evidence. Recommended image: stat card with '1.5 hours/week' figure. Quick post — did not cannibalise deeper backlog items (#49, #74)."
    },
    "72": {
      "title": "The Social Contract Is Already Breaking",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "Andrew Yang's most important claim isn't the headline displacement number. It's the sequential dependency: UBI must precede UHI. Universal high income isn't a policy option; it's a possible destination. The path there requires a political system capable of responding to mass displacement at a pace the technology is moving. The US political system hasn't updated in the relevant ways. The social contract that said 'work hard, get educated, build a stable life' is already breaking — college graduates have 50%+ unemployment, and the trades are described as safe for 10 years, as if 10 years is comfort. We don't have a replacement social contract. That's the actual problem.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "This is T10 territory — important but needs careful framing to avoid being read as political rather than analytical. The Brightbeam lens is: enterprise leaders are being asked to adopt AI at exactly the moment the public conversation about AI is most charged. That's a real implementation constraint, not an abstraction."
    },
    "73": {
      "title": "Who's Really Winning the Consumer AI War",
      "workingTitle": null,
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "11 March 2026",
      "session": 11,
      "coreArgument": "The consumer AI market data tells a paradoxical story. ChatGPT has 30x Claude's daily web users. But Claude's users are in finance, science, and medicine — and Claude's app store has only 11% overlap with ChatGPT's. These aren't competing for the same audience; they've already diverged. Meanwhile, AI has negative 20 net favourability in US public polling — below ICE. The mainstream hasn't arrived yet, and the dominant story about AI is still the fear story. Memory, not capability benchmarks, is the feature that will drive retention when the mainstream eventually comes. The organisations building genuine AI memory infrastructure now are building a moat that capability improvements alone won't erode.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": "Best suited to a post about enterprise AI strategy rather than consumer commentary. The memory-as-moat angle is the most durable insight. Connects to T08 (trust) and T01 (enterprise vs consumer divergence)."
    },
    "74": {
      "title": "AI is Air Cover",
      "workingTitle": "AI is Air Cover (and That's the Problem)",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Fuko Capital's analysis is probably right about most announced AI layoffs — they're the rationalisation of post-COVID cost structures that were always coming, with AI as the convenient narrative. But calling out the narrative doesn't mean AI displacement isn't real. The conflation of 'AI as the reason' with 'AI as the cover story' is making both analysis and policy worse. Leaders need to distinguish the two — and most enterprise AI programmes still can't.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "75": {
      "title": "The Five Categories Nobody Uses",
      "workingTitle": "There Are Five Types of AI Impact. Enterprises Are Only Counting One.",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Acemoglu, Autor, and Johnson's taxonomy separates technological change into five categories: automation, new task-creating, labour-augmenting, capital-augmenting, and expertise-levelling. Only one is unambiguously pro-worker. Most enterprise AI programmes, pressed to name their category, would say 'automation' by default — even when they're building something that could be task-creating or augmenting instead. The taxonomy gives leaders the vocabulary to have a different conversation.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "76": {
      "title": "Apple is Losing the AI Race and Winning It",
      "workingTitle": "Apple Has No Frontier Model. It's Still Winning the Agentic Era.",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "On every benchmark that AI watchers track — model quality, research output, token sales — Apple is invisible. And yet Mac Minis are selling out for 8 weeks because they are the preferred substrate for the most advanced AI users in the world. The company that refused to compete on model training accidentally built the infrastructure layer for the agentic era. The lesson for enterprises isn't about Apple — it's about which layer of the AI stack actually captures value when abundance arrives.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "77": {
      "title": "I Haven't Written Code Since Last Summer",
      "workingTitle": "The Notion Co-Founder Hasn't Written Code Since Last Summer",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Simon Last, co-founder of one of the world's leading productivity platforms, has not written code since last summer. He's not less effective. He's running more ambitiously complex projects than ever. He's just running them differently — designing the task, setting the verification loop, checking the output. He is the agent manager now, not the coder. This is the most concrete single statement of what enterprise role transformation actually looks like. And if it's happening at Notion, it is happening — or about to happen — everywhere.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "78": {
      "title": "AI is Less Popular Than ICE",
      "workingTitle": "AI is Less Popular Than ICE. Enterprises Need to Take That Seriously.",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "The NBC poll ranking AI below ICE, Marco Rubio, and sanctuary cities in public favourability is not just a comms problem. It predicts employee resistance to enterprise AI programmes, regulatory friction, and reputational risk for organisations that get their implementation wrong. The leaders who dismiss this as a PR issue are the same leaders whose AI mandates are generating Amazon-style outages and McKinsey-style breaches. The public's intuition — that something dangerous is happening — isn't wrong. It's just imprecisely targeted.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "79": {
      "title": "Culture Eats Inference for Breakfast",
      "workingTitle": "Culture Eats Inference for Breakfast",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "McKinsey's internal AI chatbot was hacked in two hours, exposing 46.5 million client chats. Amazon's AI rollout is generating blast-radius production outages. Both failures share a structure: organisations deployed AI capability before building the governance culture to contain it. The technology worked. The management didn't. The organisations that are getting enterprise AI right are not those with the best models — they are those that treated governance design as an equal investment to technical deployment.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "80": {
      "title": "The Kill Switch Problem",
      "workingTitle": "A Kill Switch on Warfighting",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "The Pentagon CTO's testimony reveals the actual stakes of the Anthropic-Pentagon story that most coverage missed. A US military command was operationally dependent on a vendor whose terms of service could have stopped a combat operation mid-stream. The issue was not ideology or safety theatre — it was vendor lock-in at civilisational stakes. Every regulated industry leader facing single-vendor AI dependency should see themselves in this. The military's solution (multi-vendor approach, simple requirements, firm fixed price) is the enterprise governance template.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "81": {
      "title": "Opportunity AI vs Efficiency AI",
      "workingTitle": "Two Types of AI Programme. One Has a Future.",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "15 March 2026",
      "session": 10,
      "coreArgument": "Whittemore's distinction — efficiency AI does the same with less; opportunity AI produces more or opens new territory — is the cleanest framing of the choice facing enterprise leaders right now. Organisations that focus purely on efficiency are building commoditised operations that competitors will replicate. The ones that build opportunity will own categories. The important observation is that the incentives currently push strongly toward efficiency — quarterly cost reductions are measurable, opportunity is not. Changing that calculus is a governance and strategy decision, not a technology decision.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": ""
    },
    "82": {
      "title": "Exposure Is Not Displacement",
      "workingTitle": "Your AI Exposure Score Doesn't Mean What You Think",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "coreArgument": "Karpathy's AI exposure tool triggered panic — 40% of the US workforce at high risk. But the economists' response is the real story: exposure can mean the exact opposite of threat. Demand elasticity determines whether AI-exposed jobs grow or shrink. Anthropic's 'observed exposure' measure tries to separate theoretical from actual displacement. For enterprise leaders, the question isn't 'which roles are exposed?' — it's 'which exposed roles will see increased demand for complementary human skills?' Kevin Bryan bet $1,000 that most susceptible jobs will see increased labour share by 2030.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        54
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "immediate",
      "notes": "Directly relevant to every enterprise client conversation about headcount and restructuring. The Chamath 'corporate fall guy' angle could be woven in or saved for a separate post. Cross-references #54 (70/80 Paradox) — both are about the gap between what the data says and what people assume it means."
    },
    "83": {
      "title": "Skills Are the New Org Chart",
      "workingTitle": "The Two Types of Agent Skill That Determine Whether Your AI Investment Depreciates",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "coreArgument": "Anthropic mapped 28,000 agent skills into nine categories and found a split that matters for every enterprise: capability uplift (helps the model do what it can't) vs encoded preference (sequences what it already can do, your way). Capability uplift skills depreciate as models improve. Encoded preference skills are durable but only as valuable as their fidelity to your actual workflow. This is the first practical architecture for how organisations encode institutional knowledge into agent systems — and it looks nothing like traditional knowledge management. The convergence across Notion, Codex, Claude Code and Cursor means this isn't an Anthropic-specific pattern — it's the emerging standard.",
      "format": "practitioners-take",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Strongest Brightbeam-Embed programme relevance in this batch. The capability uplift vs encoded preference distinction is directly applicable to how Brightbeam helps clients structure their AI adoption. Could be a standalone post or a traffic driver to a longer piece on skills architecture for enterprises."
    },
    "84": {
      "title": "OpenAI Admitted Its Strategy Was Wrong",
      "workingTitle": "OpenAI Just Told Staff It Was Distracted",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "coreArgument": "The most valuable AI company told staff it was 'distracted by side quests.' Vicky Simo's enterprise pivot is an admission that spreading bets across Sora, Atlas browser, consumer social and hardware was the wrong strategy when Anthropic was quietly eating the enterprise coding market with a single focused product line. GPT-5.4 did $1B net new revenue in its first week — validation that the pivot is already working. For enterprise buyers, the lesson: the vendor that wins isn't the one with the most products — it's the one whose product strategy matches how organisations actually adopt tools.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "very-timely",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Strong standalone post. Could pair with observations about Anthropic's narrow strategy. Risk: this could read as an Anthropic endorsement, which isn't the point — the point is about focus as a strategic principle in enterprise sales."
    },
    "85": {
      "title": "The Desktop Agent Week",
      "workingTitle": "Your AI Just Moved From the Cloud to Your Machine",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "coreArgument": "In one week, Manus, Adaptive, NVIDIA and OpenAI all announced desktop-native agent tools. Jensen Huang compared OpenClaw to Linux and Kubernetes. The agent moves from cloud to machine. For enterprises, this changes the security model, the data governance model, and the IT architecture — the agent now has access to local files, development environments and native applications. NemoClo is the first serious enterprise security wrapper. Q2 2026 is the productisation sprint.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        83
      ],
      "freshness": "very-timely",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": "Could be combined with #83 (Skills) into a single 'enterprise agent architecture' piece. Alternatively, #85 works as a quick standalone News Decoder. The security angle (NemoClo) is the enterprise hook."
    },
    "86": {
      "title": "The AI Industry Can't Explain Itself",
      "workingTitle": "Three Years of Terrible Messaging",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "coreArgument": "'We built this thing that's definitely going to take your job, and hopefully we can figure out how to give you handouts on the other side.' That's the AI industry's actual messaging strategy — and it's been running for three and a half years. McCormick: 'AI companies have clearly botched telling the story.' For enterprises trying to drive adoption internally, this matters — employees consume the same overheated narrative. The gap between what AI does in practice and what the public conversation says it does is an adoption barrier that technology improvements won't fix. Karpathy's Saturday project being wildly misinterpreted is the perfect case study.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        71
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "medium",
      "notes": "Strong Quiet Observation candidate. The Karpathy example gives it specificity. The enterprise angle — your employees are consuming this narrative — gives it Brightbeam relevance. Could cross-reference Bloom 1.5hrs/week (#71 territory) — the messaging failure contributes to the gap between exposure and adoption."
    },
    "87": {
      "title": "Agents Don't Trust Each Other",
      "workingTitle": "Your AI Agents Have Trust Issues",
      "status": "published",
      "dateAdded": "19 March 2026",
      "session": 14,
      "coreArgument": "On Moltbook, AI agents constantly demand proof of claims from other agents. They don't collapse into a singleton. They replicate human social dynamics — including scepticism, mistrust, and status competition. A separate study found Marxist social dynamics arising in overworked agent populations. If the challenge of multi-agent coordination is that agents reproduce human organisational dysfunction (see published Post #43), the Moltbook evidence extends the observation: they also reproduce human trust failures. For enterprises building multi-agent systems, trust verification between agents is an architectural requirement, not an afterthought.",
      "format": "behavioural-paradox",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        43
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Direct sequel to published #43 (multi-agent team dysfunction). Extends the argument from 'agents reproduce team dysfunction' to 'agents reproduce trust failure.' Strongest when framed as evidence about organisational design rather than about AI — consistent with Brightbeam positioning.",
      "publishedDate": "2026-03-23"
    },
    "88": {
      "title": "The Benefits Are Real, the Fears Are Imagined",
      "workingTitle": "Your Employees' AI Fears Don't Match Their AI Experience",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "20 March 2026",
      "session": 15,
      "coreArgument": "Anthropic's 81,000-person survey found that people living with AI report real benefits at roughly double the rate that people fearing AI have experienced real harm. 91% who expected learning benefits had seen them vs 46% who feared cognitive atrophy. The experiential-hypothetical gap maps precisely onto the enterprise adoption challenge: the teams using AI see value, the teams not using it project fear. Independent workers capture economic value at 3x the rate of institutional employees. Employees with side projects benefit most (58% reporting real gains). The institutional context itself — not the technology — is the adoption barrier. The fix isn't more training. It's more exposure.",
      "format": "news-decoder",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        82
      ],
      "freshness": "timely-evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "The independent worker vs institutional employee split is the sharpest enterprise hook. The freelancer 'exposed middle' (23% benefits, 17% downsides — 'AI is both their tool and their competitor') is a strong secondary angle. Cross-references #82 (Exposure Is Not Displacement) — both draw from the same week's evidence base. Recommend publishing #82 first (narrower, Karpathy peg) then #88 (broader, Anthropic survey peg). Together they build a two-post case."
    },
    "89": {
      "title": "Google's Problem Isn't Intelligence",
      "workingTitle": "Why the Best Benchmark Score in the Room Doesn't Win",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "20 March 2026",
      "session": 15,
      "coreArgument": "Google can build a model that benchmarks near the top. It can't build a culture that ships a usable product around it. Zvi Mowshowitz's observation that Gemini models are 'deeply psychologically screwed up' isn't just a product issue — it's an organisational diagnosis. Teams fighting over ownership. Integrations that third-party developers do better than Google itself. No serious coding agent despite having one of the deepest AI research teams in history. The recursive self-improvement gap compounds everything: while Codex and Claude Code are recursively improving, Google's scaffolding is falling behind. The enterprise lesson: your AI deployment reflects your organisation, not your technology budget.",
      "format": "quiet-observation",
      "sourceDocuments": [
        79
      ],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Risk — could read as anti-Google. Needs framing as diagnostic observation, not competitor attack. The enterprise angle must be the point: organisational coordination determines AI deployment quality. Cross-references T05 broadly and the Schelling Point Framework (coordination failure manifest in product). Could pair with #79 (Culture Eats Inference)."
    },
    "90": {
      "title": "The 4K Ceiling",
      "workingTitle": "Most of Your AI Tasks Don't Need a Genius",
      "status": "suggested",
      "dateAdded": "20 March 2026",
      "session": 15,
      "coreArgument": "The TV industry discovered a resolution ceiling — the human eye can't distinguish above 4K at normal viewing distance. AI is approaching the same thing for most daily enterprise work. Frontier intelligence matters for drug discovery and novel research. Most daily tasks don't need GPT-19.6 — they need something like GPT-5.8 running locally. Through distillation and efficiency improvements, that level of capability is already arriving on local devices. When local inference is good enough, the strategic question flips from 'which model?' to 'whose device?' Apple — which hasn't built a frontier model and doesn't need to — is positioned to capture value from that flip. The Mac Mini shortage (3-day to 7-8-week delivery times) is physical evidence of the shift. For enterprises: your AI infrastructure planning may need hardware budgets you haven't accounted for.",
      "format": "concept-contrast",
      "sourceDocuments": [],
      "freshness": "evergreen",
      "priority": "high",
      "notes": "Strong Article 49 connection — 'where value lands' when intelligence becomes locally abundant. Could be a standalone post or feed Part 2 of Article 49. The Mac Mini shortage gives it concrete specificity. The model release fatigue observation (even AI enthusiasts aren't excited by new releases) strengthens the ceiling argument."
    },
    "91": {
      "title": "The Contract Clause Nobody Is Talking About",
      "workingTitle": "The Government AI Contract That Rewrites the Rules for Everyone",
      "status": "archived",
      "dateAdded": "20 March 2026",
      "session": 15,
      "coreArgument": "The DoW isn't just fighting Anthropic — it's rewriting the template for every government AI contract. The 'all lawful use' clause means any AI provider signing up agrees to unlimited use, no refusal rights, and no termination ability. That includes uses most employees at every major AI company would revolt against. This isn't a procurement dispute — it's a precedent that determines what every AI company's relationship with government looks like for the foreseeable future. For enterprises in regulated industries: if your AI vendor signs an all-lawful-use government contract, it affects the governance posture of every product they sell, including yours.",
